<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Can be Transmitted through Breastfeeding: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS virus HIV-1 can be
transmitted to babies after birth through breastfeeding, French
doctors reported Friday in the Lancet medical journal.
</P>
<P>
Dr Valeriane Leroy and colleagues from Bordeaux, France, said
that they have studied the frequency of such infection in
developed and developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Children involved in the research were from Europe, USA,
Rwanda, Kenya, and the Ivory Coast. All children were uninfected
at two and a half months of age.
</P>
<P>
Of children in the developed countries, researchers found that
less than five percent overall were breastfed and no children were
infected with HIV-1.
</P>
<P>
However, in the developing countries, in which breastfeeding is
normal, HIV-1 infection occurred in about five percent of all
children.
</P>
<P>
"If breastfeeding had stopped at age four months, transmission
would have occurred in no infants," the researchers calculated.
</P>
<P>
The findings has important implications for public-health
strategies in developing countries, the doctors said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
