<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reducing Risk of Prostate Cancer With Selenium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Researchers from Harvard
University said eating food rich in mineral selenium may help men
ward off advanced prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
By a study of 33,737 men, they found higher selenium levels
were associated with a reduced risk of advanced prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
In the study, 81 cases of advanced prostate cancer, were
diagnosed in the test group from 1990 through 1994. After
adjusting for such factors as age, weight, vasectomy, diabetes,
smoking and family history, they found that men with the highest
selenium levels had only about one-third the likelihood of
developing advanced prostate cancer as those with low selenium.
</P>
<P>
Selenium is found in minute amounts in meat, fish, whole
grains, dairy products and vegetables grown in selenium-rich soil.
</P>
<P>
Cancer of the prostate causes nearly 40,000 deaths annually
in the United States. The gland produces fluids that form part
of semen.The cancer usually occurs in older men and often grows
slowly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
