<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Lending Rises to Spark Fears of Interest Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Lending by banks and building
societies shot up in July in Britain, sparking fears of another
interest rate rise, according to newly released figures.
</P>
<P>
The British Bankers' Association (BBA) said lending had reached
its highest point all year, while the Building Societies
Association (BSA) said more mortgages were approved in July than
in any other month this year.
</P>
<P>
July is usually a boom month for house sales, but London's
financial City had been expecting the figures to drop in response
to higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
David Smith, analyst at William de Broe, was quoted by local
media as saying: "This has really shocked the City. It is a total
reversal of the downward trend in bank lending and the new figures
certainly suggest the possibility of an adjustment in interest
rates."
</P>
<P>
Many economists said the continued strength of borrowing would
concern the Bank of England but that might not be enough on its
own to force another rate hike.
</P>
<P>
David Coleman at CIBC Wood Gundy said: "This reinforces our
suspicion that at best, monetary policy could be on hold for some
time to come."
</P>
<P>
Growth in the amount of money stored in bank and savings
accounts - M4 broad money supply - accelerated to 10 percent on an
annual basis in July from 9 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
However, it is no longer a key indicator for the Bank of
England due to its erratic nature, according to analysts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
