<HEADLINE> India Responds Cautiously to US Air strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- India Friday responded
cautiously to the attacks by the United States on alleged
terrorist bases in Afghanistan and Sudan, and underscored the need
for collective efforts by all countries to combat international
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to comment on the U.S. action," said a spokesman
for the External Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
But he added: "It is high time for the international community
to get together to tackle the problems of trans-national and
trans-border terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Officials here said that there was a provision in international
law for reprisal raids, but they declined to state whether the
American attacks in retaliation for bombings of U.S. embassies in
East Africa were justified.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said India had always highlighted the need to
tackle the menace of international terrorism globally and find a
lasting long-term solution to effectively put an end to it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police Friday enhanced security at the U.S. embassy
and other American institutions in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
City Police Commissioner V. N. Singh said that security had
been beefed up in view of the large number of Afghan refugees and
African students in the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
