<HEADLINE> Benefit Performance Raises 1.1 Billion Yuan for Flood Victims (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A large benefit performance
hosted by the ministries of Culture and Civil Affairs has raised
nearly 1.1 billion yuan (133 million U.S. dollars) for China's
flood victims, Fan Baojun, vice-minister of civil affairs,
announced here this evening.
</P>
<P>
The two-hour performance titled "Join Our Hands to Build A New
Great Wall," was staged in the Great Hall of the People in
downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Four donation hot lines which were opened for the performance
received 565 phone calls bringing some 403 million yuan in
donations, Fan said.
</P>
<P>
He added that during the past few days since news of the
performance was released, the ministry received some 690 million
yuan in domestic and foreign donations.
</P>
<P>
Many celebrities in China's entertainment and performing arts
circles participated in the performance, which was broadcast live
by China Central Television (CCTV).
</P>
<P>
The largest donation tonight came from northeast China's
Liaoning Province, China's old industrial base and a center of
financially troubled state-owned enterprises. Despite its own
problems, such as laid-off workers and an economic slowdown, the
province donated 91 million yuan (11 million US dollars) to the
flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Ma Junren, China's most famous coach of long-distance running,
and Sang Lan, a young gymnast who injured her spine at this year's
Goodwill Games and is still receiving treatment in the United
States, donated 200,000 yuan and 10,000 yuan, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
