<HEADLINE> Benefit Performance Raises 1.1 Billion Yuan for Flood Victims (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The performance was the first hosted by China's central
government departments since the country was hit by the worst
flooding in decades early this summer.
</P>
<P>
The Great Hall of the People, meeting place for China's
paramount power organ -- the National People's Congress --
provided the performance site free of charge.
</P>
<P>
Since early June, serious flooding caused by unusually heavy
rain, has plagued a dozen provinces in South China and along the
Yangtze River, as well as north China's Heilongjiang and Jilin
provinces and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the Civil Affairs Ministry in early
August put the death toll caused by the floods at more than 2,000,
adding that the number of flood victims nationwide exceeded 240
million.
</P>
<P>
Starting in July, domestic and foreign assistance for the
flooded areas has been pouring in to the Ministry of Civil Affairs
and non-governmental organizations such as the China Charity
Federation and the Red Cross Society of China.
</P>
<P>
Donations to the flood-stricken areas, excluding those received
during the performance this evening, have surpassed 1.6 billion
yuan (193 million U.S. dollars), according to the Civil Affairs
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
News media around the country have reported that many more
benefit performances or donation-raising events are expected to be
presented by local governments or social groups in coming days.
</P>
</TEXT>
