<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harbin Battling Against Water Seeping Through Embankments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Frogmen of the Chinese Navy were
mobilized today to block seepage from the levees surrounding
Harbin, the largest heavy-industrial center in northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
More than 120,000 civilians were transferred to safe places
today before the arrival of a third flood peak on the Songhua
River.
</P>
<P>
At 7:00 this afternoon, the water level on the Songhua River
hit 120.84 meters, 2.74 meters above the danger level and 0.79
meters above the 1957 record. The city also recorded a record flow
rate of 17,200 cubic meters per second today.
</P>
<P>
Levees surrounding Harbin are considered to be the best in
Heilongjiang. Nonetheless, bags containing rocks, flour, earth and
lime were the last major defense against floodwaters penetrating
river embankments.
</P>
<P>
Surging water in the Songhua River seeped through the primary
and secondary embankments, with water levels as deep as 20
centimeters on many streets. Soldiers used plastic bowls to
throw seeping water back into the river.
</P>
<P>
More than 400,000 soldiers and civilians battled surging water
by placing sandbags atop the levees.
</P>
<P>
Streets near the Songhua River were filled with trucks hauling
plastic bags and stones to workers on the levees.
</P>
<P>
Volunteers supplied weary workers with food, including stuffed
buns and gruel to provide relief from the summer heat.
</P>
<P>
Liang Guanglie, Shenyang Military Area Commander, and Yang
Fuchen, commander of a PLA group army, were present on the front
lines today in the battle against seepage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
