<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Army to Tackle Hezbollah Roadside Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Upset by the rising death of
its soldiers in South Lebanon, Israeli army has decided to tackle
the renewed use of roadside bombs by Hezbollah guerrillas, Israel
Radio reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
One Israeli soldier and one civilian working for the army were
killed late Thursday by Hezbollah (Party of God) guerrillas in
South Lebanon, less than 48 hours after two roadside bombs claimed
the life of one Israeli soldier and wounded four others.
</P>
<P>
The two Israelis were driving a truck in the Israeli
self-claimed South Lebanon Security Zone when a roadside bomb was
detonated through remote control by the Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Chief of
General Staff Shaul Mofaz visited the zone Friday for the second
time in the past week.
</P>
<P>
The radio said Israeli army officials would study ways to deal
with the renewed use of roadside bombs by Hezbollah, which has
been fighting to oust Israeli troops from the
1200-square-kilometer security Zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel created the zone in 1985 to allegedly protect its
northern border towns from cross-border attacks by Lebanese
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said Thursday that
Israel was trying to find a solution to pull out its troops from
South Lebanon, calling it "a major goal" of his government.
</P>
<P>
The deaths Thursday night brought to 12 the death toll of the
Israelis who have been killed in South Lebanon since the
beginning of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
