<HEADLINE> Clinton Talks With Pakistan PM on Telephone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
telephoned Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif Friday evening to
convey his administration's point of view on the overnight missile
attacks on alleged terrorist bases in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
A press release by the Foreign Minister said Sharif told
Clinton that the unilateral U.S. action constituted violation of
the sovereignty and territorial integrity of independent states.
</P>
<P>
The attacks had caused anguish and indignation in Pakistan,
Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
Instead of resorting to military action against sovereign
states, the U.S. should have opted for dialogue and consultation
to achieve its objectives, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
The prime Minister also reiterated Pakistan's strong commitment
to combating terrorism in all its forms, as it had itself been a
victim of state-sponsored terrorism for many years.
</P>
<P>
In a separate press release, the Pakistani Foreign Ministry
said its spokesman has clarified that no casualty has occurred
inside Pakistani territory as believed earlier, nor has any damage
been caused on the Pakistani side of the border.
</P>
<P>
An earlier announcement in this regard was based on inaccurate
information, the press released said.
</P>
<P>
All casualties and damage, as a result of the U.S. strikes,
have occurred across the border inside Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
