<HEADLINE> Britain Opposes Foreign Intervention in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Labor government made
clear Friday Britain was opposed to foreign intervention in the
Democratic Republic of Congo while the African country's domestic
violence continued worsening.
</P>
<P>
A British Foreign Office spokeswoman was quoted by Reuters as
saying Friday that Britain was against any foreign intervention as
"the break-up of Congo could engender violence and instability
throughout the region for many years ahead."
</P>
<P>
"A settlement imposed from outside or by force of arms will not
produce lasting stability nor the conditions for prosperity and
democracy," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the SADC (South African Development Community), the
Organization of African Unity and and other players will now act
together to help broker and implement a peace agreement
acceptable to all," she added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South African President Nelson Mandela has called on
Zimbabwe, Rwanda, Uganda and Congo to hold a meeting Saturday to
discuss the latest situation in Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
