<HEADLINE> Two Men Still in Custody for Questioning After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Northern Irish police were still
questioning two men on Friday who were allegedly involved in the
Omagh bombing that killed 28 people last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"There are now two people still in custody," a police spokesman
said in Northern Ireland capital Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said that under anti-guerrilla laws, the pair
could be detained until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Three others arrested with them last Monday were released on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Real IRA, a breakaway group opposed to a truce by the
mainstream Irish Republican Army, claimed responsibility to the
bombing, the deadliest atrocity in 30-year conflict in the British
province.
</P>
<P>
To hunt down the bombers, police have appealed for information
about two men who were seen 40 minutes before the blast, leaving a
car at the busy junction where it exploded.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said they had been seen by several
witnesses. The authorities wanted to hear from anyone who had
seen the vehicle being driven or parked in the market town.
</P>
</TEXT>
