<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Warns of Cremation Crisis in The UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A shortage of doctors willing to
take on specialist work for crematoriums could lead to funerals
being delayed in the UK, the British Medical Association has
warned.
</P>
<P>
Professor Stuart Horner, from the University of Central
Lancashire, said Friday in the British Medical Journal that "the
present system is about to collapse under the impending manpower
crisis."
</P>
<P>
The legislative framework for cremation in the UK was
established in 1902. It requires the signature of a medical
referee in order that cremation can take place.
</P>
<P>
Cremation now accounts for 73 percent of disposals of dead
bodies in the UK.
</P>
<P>
After conducting a survey of doctors currently working as
medical referees for crematoriums, Professor Horner found that
eighty percent of the referees are over the age of 50 years and a
third are over 65.
</P>
<P>
Another survey conducted at a crematorium in the north of
England also found that less than 41 percent of the cremation
documentation had been completed sufficiently, thus requiring
further investigation which could delay the cremation process.
</P>
<P>
"We are teetering on the brink of a crisis. Increasingly there
are days at crematoriums when no medical referee is available."
Professor Horner said.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that younger doctors may be discouraged from
becoming a medical referee because the work "requires challenging
colleagues about their standards of care form time to time."
</P>
<P>
There is also the issue of the "derisory fee", which is only
2.70 pounds (4.40 U.S. dollars) for completing a cremation, and
referees often have to pay their own travelling expenses when they
attend a crematorium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
