<HEADLINE> China's 'Silicon Valley Times' Celebrates First Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- "Silicon Valley Times," a
periodical to promote cultural and scientific exchanges between
China and other countries, celebrated its first publication in
Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The publication of the magazine was launched by visiting Chinese
students in Silicon Valley near San Francisco and overseas Chinese
scientists working in the United States, according to Shen Jian,
editor-in-chief of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
The Fujian Provincial Scientific and Technological Commission,
the China International Cultural Exchange Center, the Chinese
Embassy in the United States and the American-Sino Relations
Committee have given full support to the founding of the magazine,
Shen said.
</P>
<P>
Many associations of Chinese scientists at Stanford and Harvard
universities and in Silicon Valley and groups of Chinese students
visiting in the United States also provided help during the
creation of the magazine, Shen said.
</P>
<P>
Experts attending today's first-issue celebration agreed that
the information revolution originating in Silicon Valley in the
San Francisco Bay area has brought about great change in the
economic, political, military and cultural activities of the human
race.
</P>
<P>
People's lives will be greatly changed because of the creation
of information technologies, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Daohan, chairman of the Association for Relations Across
the Taiwan Straits, was invited to be general consultant to the
magazine. About 100 representatives from all walks of life and
overseas diplomats in Beijing attended today's celebration.
</P>
