<HEADLINE> Rwanda Blasts SADC Military Aid to Kabila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda Friday expressed its
regret over the intervention of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) forces to rescue President Laurent Kabila of the
Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The Rwanda News Agency quoted a government statement as saying
that Rwanda regretted that some SADC member states "have decided
to support President Laurent Kabila and not the Congolese people,
by sending military forces to his rescue."
</P>
<P>
It said it reserved the right to get involved in a conflict in
the Democratic Republic of Congo "in whatever manner it deems
appropriate" and condemned Zimbabwe's call for military
intervention there.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan government accused Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe, chairman of SADC organ on politics, defense and security,
of having thrown all his support to Kabila "for his personal
interests".
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed by Patrick Mazimhaka, Minister in the
President's Office, asserted that Rwanda has stakes in the
Congolese war as far as peace and stability for itself and other
countries of the sub-region are concerned.
</P>
<P>
"Stability in Congo benefits not only Congo, but also its
neighbors and Rwanda in particular," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
In view of the involvement of the SADC members in Congo and
the lack of prior consultation with Democratic Congo's immediate
neighbors, Rwanda said that it will be dragged into the
three-week crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Rwanda, therefore, reserves the right to get involved and to
assist the Congolese people in their search for a lasting
solution in whatever manner it deems appropriate," the statement
warned.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Kigali believe that President Mugabe is the brain
behind the intervention of SADC frorces on the side of President
Kabila, despite all sorts of abuses he has been accused of by his
opponents.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources there also claimed that Mugabe has a
business deal worth 195 million U.S. Dollars with DRC President
Kabila that he must safeguard at all costs.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Defense Minister Moven Mahachi had earlier this
week accused Rwanda of invading Congo. And Zimbabwean President
Mugabe said Thursday that Rwanda was directly involved in the
Tutsi-led rebellion in democratic Congo according to results
concluded by the fact-finding commission of SADC foreign
ministers.
</P>
<P>
However, Rwanda said that the accusations were biased as long
as the inquiry c/mmission set up by seven African leaders on
August 8 in Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe, had not yet made public its
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
President Mugabe's move to raise SADC forces to assist Kabila
against his foes was "not only wrong in principle, but it is
fraudulent in nature," said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
