<HEADLINE> Cyprus Dismisses Turkish Press Reports on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus on Friday dismissed the
Turkish press reports that the U.S. has put forward a new proposal
on breaking the one-year-old deadlock in the Cyprus peace process.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's media recently reported that in the proposal, the
U.S. urged Turkey to withdraw its demand for recognizing the
breakaway Turkish Cypriot regime in northern Cyprus in return for
Cyprus' halt to accession talks with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
"The said articles appear to be untrue and this is also
reflected in statements by the U.S. envoy for Cyprus," government
spokesman Christos Stylianides said at his daily press briefing
here.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Ankara last week, U.S. State Department
Coordinator for Cyprus Thomas Miller reportedly proposed to create
a no-fly zone over Cyprus in exchange for Cyprus' cancellation of
its plan to deploy Russian-made anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
But Turkish press reports said Miller's demand was rejected by
the Turkish government, and he left Ankara empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides insisted that Cyprus' integration process with the
EU was a completely separate issue that should not be related to
the resumption of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus would not give Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash anything in exchange for his return to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
He urged Denktash to comply with U.N. Security Council's
resolutions and appeals of the international community to return
to the negotiating table without preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops took over the northern third of the island in the wake of
a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace process broke down last August when Denktash
quited the talks to protest the EU decision to start membership
talks with Cyprus instead of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He has conditioned his return to the negotiations on the halt
of Cyprus' EU talks and the recognition of his regime in northern
Cyprus that was declared in 1983.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the divided
island in a bizonal and bicommunal federation through peace talks,
but so far no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
