<HEADLINE> Roundup: 26 People Killed in U.S. Missile Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- At least 26 people were killed
and 30 others injured when U.S. cruise missiles exploded Thursday
night on the Zhawar Kili Albadr base near Khost, about 150 km
southeast of the Afghan capital Kabul, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. forces on Thursday launched missile attacks against
suspected terrorist bases in Afghanistan allegedly run by Osama
Bin Laden, an anti-American Islamic militant who has been blamed
for bombing the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania early this
month.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. retaliation "is such a callous act," said Taliban
spokesman Wakil Ahmed Akhumzada at the militia's headquarters in
the southern city of Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
He added that the U.S. had no proof against Laden, according to
reports reaching here from Kabul.
</P>
<P>
He also said the U.S. missiles hit targets near Jalalabad,
about 100 km east of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The reports also quoted officials in Jalalabad as saying that
three people were killed in the attack. However, U.S. defense
officials had said that only the Albadr base was targeted, and six
sites were hit on the sprawling complex.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, News Network International, an independent Pakistani
news agency, quoted the Karkat ul Mujahideen group as saying that
five of its Pakistani members were killed at the camp near Khost.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan-based Harkat ul Mujahideen, formally known as
Harkatul Ansar, was included last year in the U.S. State
Department's list of terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban said after the U.S. missile attack that Laden was
safe and no damage had been done to any of his companions.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Taliban militia, Mulla Mohammad Omar, denounced
the attack as "a brazen manifestation of enmity against the Afghan
nation."
</P>
<P>
"It is not only an attack against Osma bin Laden but also an
attack against the entire people in Afghanistan," he told the
Pakistan-based Afghan Islamic Press from his base at Kandahar
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Omar said the Taliban had repeatedly given categorical
assurances that Laden was not involved in any terrorist activities
from the Afghan soil and that they were ready to protect him.
</P>
<P>
"We will never hand over Osama bin Laden to anyone," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Laden, son of a wealthy Saudi construction magnate, is believed
to have used his fortune to run the camps. He has been living in
Afghanistan with the permission of the Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Speculation about a possible U.S. attack had been fueled by the
evacuation a day earlier of all but essential embassy staff in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, one media report from Kabul said that a group of
unidentified gunmen seriously injured two U.N. officials in Kabul
early Friday, a day after the U.S. missile attack on the alleged
terrorist bases in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Prayer leaders at mosques in Kabul and Kandahar, the Taliban's
stronghold, exhorted the faithful to protest the U.S. missile
strikes.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of angry Afghans took to the streets in Kabul and
Kandahar Friday protesting the U.S. missile attack on their
country.
</P>
<P>
The bazaars and shops in Kandahar were shut in protest.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan on Friday expressed "indignation" over the U.S.
missile attacks on alleged terrorist facilities in Afghanistan and
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said in a statement that he was
not aware of any violation of his country's airspace. However, "it
is being investigated," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government of Pakistan, Aziz said, "expresses its
indignation over the attacks" no matter what justifications were
given. "The people of Pakistan are justifiably outraged over the
act," he added.
</P>
<P>
Aziz also reiterated that Pakistan is against terrorism, as it
has been a victim of terrorism including state-sponsored
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan, like in the past, will continue to support
the cause of fighting international terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
