<HEADLINE> India's First Pollution-free Bus Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- India's first pollution-free
bus to run on compressed natural gas (CNG) was launched here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bus, with an engine imported from the American manufacturer
"Cummins", will be run by the Delhi Transport Corporation (DTC) on
a trial basis from Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a beginning in our efforts to replace the entire DTC
fleet by CNG vehicles by the year 2001 as directed by the Supreme
Court," Delhi Transport Minister Rajendra Gupta said after
receiving the bus from its manufacturer TELCO.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was aimed at making New Delhi pollution
free by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
TELCO General Manager Ram Nath said the bus has the engine in
the rear, power steering and the hydraulic door closing system.
</P>
<P>
Nath said his company would start mass production of the bus,
worth 150 million rupees (some 3.8 million U.S. dollars) each,
after a green signal is given by the government. The cost would be
much lower since engines would be indigenously made, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
