<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Warned to Avoid Alcohol When Trying to Conceive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Women who are trying to conceive
should avoid drinking any alcohol, according to a new research
published Friday in the British Medical Journal.
</P>
<P>
Although it has long been known that women who drink heavily
take longer to become pregnant, researchers from Denmark have found
for the first time that even moderate drinking can affect a
woman's chances of conceiving.
</P>
<P>
Dr Tina Kold Jensen from the National University Hospital in
Denmark and colleagues studied 430 Danish couples aged 20-35
years, who were trying to have a baby for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The researchers found that those women drinking one to five
units (a unit is a glass of wine or half pint of beer) were a
third less likely to conceive within six months than those who
drank nothing.
</P>
<P>
Those who drank six to ten units a week reduced their chances
by almost half, and those who drank more than ten units cut their
chances by two thirds.
</P>
<P>
"This finding needs further corroboration," the researchers
concluded, "but it seems reasonable to encourage women to reduce
their intake of alcohol or do not drink at all when they are
trying to become pregnant." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Sees U.S. Strikes as "Unilateral Action" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Pakistani
diplomat on Friday described the U.S. missile attacks on Sudan and
Afghanistan as "the unilateral action which goes against the
sovereignty of member states of the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Kamal, Pakistan's permanent representative to the United
Nations, told reporters here that "the unilateral action has been
taken in what appears to be an international problem," and "an
international problem requires international response."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan remains firmly oppose to terrorism in all its forms
and continues to back all efforts against terrorism, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Pakistani envoy voiced his fear that "unilateral
actions of this type might increase the oppose tide of terrorism
in the world."
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, the Pakistani foreign minister, via the
nation's U.N. mission here, issued a written statement, saying
that "Pakistan takes a serious view of this unilateral action of
the U.S. involving the use of force against sovereign countries in
violation of the recognized principles and norms of inter-state
conduct, which constitutes a dangerous precedent."
</P>
<P>
Five or six civilians were killed Thursday after a U.S. missile
went astray into Pakistan, rather than its original target in the
neighboring Afghanistan, said Kamal.
</P>
<P>
"We suffered from terrorism on the one hand, and we suffered
from the (U.S.) reaction" on the other hand, he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton on Thursday ordered missile strikes
on Sudan and Afghanistan in response of the twin bombings on
August 7 in Kenya and Tanzania. The bombings killed 257 people
and injured more than 5,000 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
