<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Asia Strives to Bring Women into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 21 (Xinhua) -- In South Asia, where
socio-cultural discrimination against women prevails, progress has
been made in efforts to achieve the ultimate goal of bringing
women into the mainstream of development with independence and
equality.
</P>
<P>
At their inaugural meeting in December 1985, leaders of the
seven-nation South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC) emphasized that women should increasingly participate in
activities at the regional level and that programs and projects be
devised to ensure their active participation in the development
process.
</P>
<P>
"The primary focus of the social sector for the member
countries has been the conditions of women and children, and the
priority attached by the member countries to women and children is
uplifting their status," said Director Kunzang C. Namgyel at the
Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
"For women, we have a plan of action, the basic objective of it
is to improve the social and economic conditions of women,
eliminate gender discrimination in areas of education, health,
nutrition, employment, and to ensure that they have equal access
to resources and services," she told Xinhua in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
The regional plan of action adopted in December 1993 called for
national policies and distinct programs for women, as well as
special training programs for gender awareness to senior
policy-makers and planners in all ministries.
</P>
<P>
It also recommended that qualified women be given key positions
at policy and decision-making levels in economic and planning
ministries, and measures be taken to improve coordination among
government, non-governmental organizations and other agencies to
facilitate the implementation of their plans and programs.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the plan of action called for extended credit
facilities on easy terms to women for self-employment by using
their knowledge and skills, and social mobilization through
advocacy and awareness-raising activities for achieving the
development of women in general.
</P>
<P>
Namgyel said each member country has set up women affairs
ministry to look after the well-being of women.
</P>
<P>
She said a recent meeting of the Technical Committee on Women
in Development found that most of the member countries have
incorporated gender concerns in their national development plans,
which comprise policies and programs for the advancement of women.
</P>
<P>
"Some have positive steps and provide equal opportunities for
women at decision-making level," she said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the SAARC states reserve seats for women in
national parliaments and local self-governing bodies, and there
are also pro-women legislations in the member countries --
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
She said the member countries are trying to create a safer
working environment for women and have launched vocational,
technical and educational programs for women, especially in the
rural areas to encourage them to develop their skills to make them
at least self-reliant.
</P>
<P>
In addition, special credit facilities have been set up for
women for self-employment, she said.
</P>
<P>
"They (member countries) also discourage many traditional
practices which affect women and the girl child," she continued.
"There are a lot of traditional practices which sometimes affect
not only their health status, but the general attitudes toward
women, such as child marriage and dowry."
</P>
<P>
She said there are a lot of non-governmental organizations
working together to complement the efforts of the government to
ensure that there is greater sensitization of issues relating to
women.
</P>
<P>
On the evil of trafficking in women and children, Namgyel said
that it is an area now given lots of importance by the member
countries.
</P>
<P>
She said that at their 9th summit in May 1997, SAARC leaders
emphasized the issue and expressed grave concern about it, and
they pledged to coordinate their efforts and strengthen and
strictly observe the existing legislations in member countries,
including simplification of repatriation procedures for victims of
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
At their 10th summit held last month in Colombo, Sri Lanka, the
leaders decided to sign the Regional Convention on Combating the
Crime of Trafficking in Women and Children for Prostitution at
their next summit in 1999, and suggested that the scope of the
convention be broadened to cover purposes other than prostitution.
</P>
<P>
They also recommended the exploration of the feasibility of
establishing a Regional Fund for Rehabilitation of Victims of
Trafficking in Women and Children for Prostitution on a voluntary
basis.
</P>
<P>
"This is something which I think is a big forward movement and
is the desire of member countries to address the problem
seriously," Namgyel observed.
</P>
<P>
She said South Asia has a big population of women and children
and malnutrition is definitely another area of concern.
</P>
<P>
At their 9th summit, SAARC leaders decided to examine the
possibility of a nutrition initiative to promote availability of
food of essential nutritional value to individual household and
evolve policies for supplementing and fortifying essential
micro-nutrients.
</P>
<P>
"The Technical Committee on Health has come up with a number of
proposals," Namgyel said.
</P>
<P>
She said national polices of member countries on nutrition are
being strengthened as well.
</P>
<P>
"We have noticed that it is treated more as a national problem,
and not just as a sectoral problem," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
