<HEADLINE> Egypt Renews Call for Anti-terrorism World Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt renewed a call Friday for
holding a world summit to discuss fighting terrorism in a
collective and organized way, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In response to Thursday's U.S. air raids on suspected terrorist
bases in Sudan and Afghanistan, Egypt called on the United Nations
to host a world summit on combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
It urged the U.N. Security Council to take appropriate measures
in line with the U.N. Charter to fight and root out terrorism and
bring those responsible to justice.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. launched missile attacks Thursday night on a
pharmaceutical factory near the Sudanese capital Khartoum and
suspected terrorist bases in retaliation for bombings on August 7
against its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has accused Sudan of sponsoring international
terrorism and alleged that the factory was manufacturing chemical
weapons agents that could be used by Islamic militants to launch
new attacks against U.S. targets.
</P>
<P>
Egypt reiterated its warning that organized terrorism could
inflict severe loss of human lives and properties.
</P>
<P>
It called for defining the responsibility that countries that
shelter and support terrorists should take.
</P>
<P>
Egypt itself is a victim of terrorism as Islamic militants have
been launching a terror campaign in an attempt to overthrow the
secular government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
