<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Botha Loses Battle with Special Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president P.W. Botha Friday lost his battle with the special
court, the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC), when he was
convicted for ignoring a subpoena by the TRC.
</P>
<P>
Botha was sentenced to a fine of 10,000 Rand (1,600 U.S.
Dollars) or 12 months' imprisonment for refusing to attend a TRC
hearing on the now defunct state security council (SSC), after a
protracted trial of eight months, which he chaired at the height
of the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
The regional court in George, Western Cape Province, also
sentenced the 82-year-old man to another 12 months in jail,
suspended for five years.
</P>
<P>
What the unrepentant former state president would not like to
see is the scenario that he could still be subpoenaed to appear
before the truth body, which will have its amnesvy committee
continue with hearings for at least another six months before a
total closure.
</P>
<P>
Another refusal to testify by Botha could bring his suspended
sentence into effect.
</P>
<P>
Judge Victor Lugaju said the sentence to the ailing and aged
former president was appropriate, considering that Botha had
shown no remorse throughout the trial and had ignored all the
opportunities to settle the matter amicably.
</P>
<P>
The TRC filed charges against Botha last December after he
defied three TRC subpoenas. After the court accepted the case,
the truth body made a last-ditch effort to have him testify and
settle the matter outside court, but Botha rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
The judge said Botha, who held positions from defense
minister, prime minister to state president between 1966 and
1989, should testify in person to help the TRC to find the truth
about the former government's activities.
</P>
<P>
The judge rejected Botha's arguments that the subpoena was
technically flawed, and that TRC chairman Desmond Tutu had agreed
to receive Botha's written answers of questions and spare his
personal testimony.
</P>
<P>
Wearing a grey pinstripc suit, Botha stared straight ahead
throughout proceedings, showing little emotion.
</P>
<P>
Outside the court building, about 50 demonstrators chanted:
"Send him to jail." Some held banners saying: "We can forgive him
his past, send him to jail for his arrogance."
</P>
<P>
Although the sentence was handed down, the legal tussle
between Botha and the TRC seemed far from over. Botha's lawyers
have vowed to appeal against his conviction.
</P>
<P>
TRC acting chairman Alex Boraine Friday repeated his call for
Botha to cooperate with the commission, saying the conviction had
showed no one is above the law.
</P>
<P>
Boraine said he hoped Botha could change his mind and agree to
testify if the TRC's amnesty commission needs his evidence in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Botha, who was state president between 1984 and 1989, has been
considered largely responsible for the former government's harsh
persecution of anti-apartheid activists. He was implicated in a
string of notorious bombings and assassinations of anti-apartheid
personnel.
</P>
<P>
Former law and order minister Adriaan Vlok claimed last month
that Botha personally gave the order to bomb the South African
Council of Churches headquarters at Khotso House in Johannesburg
in 1988. The blast claimed hundreds of lives and shocked the
world.
</P>
<P>
Botha's sentence drew mixed reactions from major political
parties in the country.
 |*4e National Party (NP), the biggest opposition party, and the
Freedom Front (FF), another white-based party, criticized TRC's
handling of the Botha case, saying the commission was biased.
</P>
<P>
The NP, of which Botha was leadezr between 1978 and 1989, said
the legal action could have been avoided had the TRC adopted a
more amicable approach. The NP complained before that the truth
body is too soft in dealing with members of the ruling African
National Congress (ANC) compared with apartheid government
officials.
</P>
<P>
The FF said the TRC was out to humiliate and discredit the
Afrikaner by insisting on Botha's appearance in hearings. It said
Botha could be "admired" for defqkng the truth body, despite the
risk of his being found guilty and sentenced.
</P>
<P>
However, the ANC and the Pan Africanist Congress (PAC)
welcomed the verdict, saying it was a clear message that no one
was above the law. The PAC said the conviction was "predictable"
because "everything he (Botha) had done was wrong." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
