<HEADLINE> Ugandan FM in Luanda to Explain Stance in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Foreign Minister Amama
Mbabazi said here Friday that his country "has never invaded the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)."
</P>
<P>
After talks with Angolan Prime Minister Franca van-Dunem on
the unfolding conflict in Congo, Mbabazi told reporters that
"just like other countries in the region, Uganda is concerned
about the situation in Congo."
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan foreign minister asked van-Dunem to convey a
letter from Ugandan President Yueri Museveni to Angolan President
Jose Eduardo dos Santos.
</P>
<P>
Mbabazi came to Luanda as the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) member states are split on whether to send
troops to help Congolese President Laurent Kabila vight the
Tutsi-led rebels, who are pushing toward capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Angolan Deputy Foreign Minister Jorge Chicote confirmed
Wednesday that there was a plan to help Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"We have taken a collective decision that every kind of help
should be given to President Kabila, including military support,"
said Chicote.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Angola poured troops into its northern
enclave Cabinda Friday, moving toward the border with the rebel
held Congo River corridor of the Congolese territory.
</P>
<P>
Angolan troops moved through the same territory last year to
help Kabila oust late dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the spluttering Angolan peace process, the
Uganndan foreign minister said that his government "supports the
efforts made by the Angolan government to build up peace and
normalize the political and military situation in the country."
</P>
<P>
Mbabazi dismissed as groundless the rumors saying that Uganda
has something to do with Jonas Savimbi, President of the
opposition movement National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
"My country has nothing to do with the UNITA president," the
Ugandan minister said, adding that he has only heard of the name.
</P>
<P>
After the one-day brief visit to Angola, Mbabazi will leave
for Namibia to discuss with other southern African leaders about
the current scenario in democraticgo. 
