<HEADLINE> UNHCR Evacuates Staff from Afghanistan after U.S. Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) is evacuating international
staff from Afghanistan after U.S. strikes on sites in eastern
Afghanistan and Sudan, said the U.N. agency here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Four non-American staff members were leaving the country on
Friday following a U.S. State Department warning on Tuesday of a
serious threat to non-Moslem expatriates, said UNHCR spokeswoman
Maki Shinohara at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
An American staff member had already left for neighboring
Pakistan, she said. UNHCR activities were being carried out by
local staff.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Geneva-based International Committee of the Red
Cross (ICRC) said it had pulled out about a dozen international
staff members out of Afghanistan on Thursday due to rumours of
possible reprisal attacks on aid workers.
</P>
<P>
There are now another 60 expatriate delegates of the agency
still staying in Afghanistan but they had been told to stay at
home and their work had been restricted for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC said that the Taleban authorities had expressed their
commitment to ensure the security of ICRC staff.
</P>
<P>
But two U.N. relief agencies, the World Food Program (WFP) and
the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF), said they had no immediate
evacuation plans following the U.S. missile attacks in retaliation
for the U.S. embassy bombings in East Africa that killed up to 260
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
