<HEADLINE> Rwanda Ready for War With DRC: Says Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda is ready for war
with the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) if Zimbabwe andNamibia failed to imm
ediately recall troops allegedly sent to the
DRC, Rwandan Ambassador to South Africa, Ben Karenzi, said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Karenzi as
saying that Rwandan troops are ready to go into the DRC to
protect "Rwanda's vital interest in eastern Congo."
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan ambassador said his government had information
that Hutu rebels, allegedly responsible for Rwandan genocide in
1994, are still active in eastern DRC. They are allegedly
regrouped and rearmed.
</P>
<P>
"One would like to point out that Rwanda has a very vital
interest in eastern DRC," he said. "It has an interest to
protect the safety of its people as well`as the country's
internal security."
</P>
<P>
Karenzi called on South African President Nelson Mandela to
intervene and to persuade Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe and
Namibian President Sam Nujoma into withdrawing their military
support for DRC President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"President Mandela should take the lead as Chairman of SADC
(Southern African Development Community). We expect SADC to take
full responsibility for the actions of its members."
~?According to his information, Karenzi said, Zimbabwean and
Namibian troops have already been deployed in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government was surprised by the move of the
two SADC countries.
</P>
<P>
"Kabila has declare$ himself an enemy of Rwanda. Any other
party who supports him therefore also is an enemy of Rwanda and
they might be met with Rwandan military force," Karenzi warned.
</P>
<P>
He said that although his country is completely dissatisfied
with Kabila's regime, his government supports an immediate
cease-fire to allow the DRC people to find a political solution.
</P>
<P>
"The Congo (DRC) is not just a member of the SADC, but also of
the Great Lakes Economic Community and other regional groups.
Intervention by SADC members would not necessarily benefit the
people of the Congo," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kabila accused Rwanda and Uganda of being behind rebel forces
in his country, but the two countries immediately denied the
charge.
</P>
<P>
Karenzi's war threats came one day before Mandela is to host
peace talks among the presidents of the DRC, Rwanda and Uganda in
Pretoria, followed by a SADC meeting on the crisis in centr`l
Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to SAPA, a Namibian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Friday denied Namibia's military intervention in the DRC as
alleged by Karenzi.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Permanent Secretary Tonata Emvula reiterated a
statement by President Nujoma that Namibia was looking for a
peaceful solutions.
</P>
<P>
"We are not involved militarily and never had any intention to
do so," Emvula was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Namibian Defense Minister Erkki Nghhmtina said Friday
that SADC members would not allow one of their members to be
attacked and destroyed, according to SAPA.
</P>
<P>
On his return from Botswana and Zimbabwe, the Namibian
minister said SADC would make sure that any aggressor targeting
SADC member states would think twice before carrying out such an
act.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that Namibia had pledged logistical support for
Kabila such as food and medical equipment. He neither denied nor
confirmed reports about the tons of weapons and ammunition flown
out of Namibia to the DRC at the weekend. 
</P>
