<HEADLINE> Russian Blue Chips Down 5-15 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian share prices shed another
5-15 percent in extremely thin trading on Friday as the market
waits for clarification on the planned swap of government treasury
bills.
</P>
<P>
The RTS-Interfax composite ruble index dropped 4.92 percent to
21.74, a fresh record low for this year. The RTS1-Interfax index,
which does not include Gazprom shares, went down by 5.56 percent
from the previous day's close of 81.76.
</P>
<P>
So far, the prices of the most liquid shares on the Russian
market have decreased 25-40 percent over the past week since the
government and central bank's move Monday to effectively devaluate
the ruble and suspend payment of short-term treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
The week's trade was extremely sluggish with composite RTS
turn-over standing below 40 million U.S. dollars, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The ruble further devalued Friday and the central bank set
Saturday's official exchange rate at 7.005 rubles to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The composite RTS-Interfax ruble index dropped over the week by
more than 24 percent to 21.6 points, a record low. The
RTS1-Interfax index decreased some 30 percent to 80.8 points.
</P>
<P>
Friday's Debates in the State Duma, or lower house of
parliament, which demanded President Boris Yeltsin to step down
voluntarily and threatens a no-confidence motion on the
government, further slackened the stock market.
</P>
<P>
But the fallouts of the Duma session was minimal as the results
were expected, observers say.
</P>
<P>
At closing on the Russian Trading System, Unified Energy
Systems of Russia was at 0.053/0.053 dollar, down 11.7 percent in
volume of 1q#3N(G.208 million shares; Lukoil was at 4.925/5.15
dollars, down 2.5 percent in volume of 309,000 shares; Mosenergo
was at 0.026/0.0275 dollar, down 10.3 percent with 8.89 million
shares changing hands; and Rostelecom plunged 16.7 percent to
0.75/0.875 dollar with 390,000 shares traded.
</P>
<P>
Gazprom shares on the Moscow Stock Exchange, which are included
on the RTS-Interfax composite index, dropped 16 percent to a
record low of 0.781 rubles in slim trading of 5.744 million
rubles. 
</P>
