<HEADLINE> Israel Prods PNA to Intensify Fight Against Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Following the killing of a
Jewish settler, Israel on Friday renewed its demand that the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) do more to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
A Jewish rabbi was stabbed to death Thursday night in the
flashpoint West Bank city Hebron, escalating the tension among
the settlers and Palestinian residents.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu cut short his summer
vacation in the north Friday and conferred with his aides in
Jerusalem to discuss the security of settlers.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu promised that the government would strengthen
security measures and "do everything possible" to protect Jewish
settlers in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
He accused the PNA of failing to fulfill its obligations on
fighting terrorism, while urging PNA President Yasser Arafat to
take steps to capture and punish the assailants.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers have imposed a curfew on the Tel Rumeida
Jewish neighborhood in Hebron, while Palestinian police searched
in the much larger Arabic areas for the attacker, who fled the
rabbi's home after knifing him and set fire to the house.
</P>
<P>
Hebron, where about 450 Jewish settlers live among 120,000 Arab
residents, has been a major flashpoint for the Israeli-Palestinian
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The stabbing was the second time in less than a month that
Jewish settlers were fatally attacked in the West Bank. Two Jewish
settlers were ambushed and killed on August 4 in the Yitzhar
settlement near another West Bank city of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, who visited the
home of the murdered rabbi in Hebron, accused the Palestinians of
failing to carry out their commitment to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"They must do it now," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of right-wing Israelis took part in the funeral of
the slain rabbi Friday and security was beefed up along the road
while his coffin was brought from Hebron to Jerusalem for burial.
</P>
<P>
Settlement leaders and right-wing lawmakers, criticizing the
government for not doing enough to protect Jewish settlers, urged
Netanyahu to halt the talks with the PNA on the long overdue
Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Environment Minister Rafael Eitan called on the government to
enlarge the Tel Rumeida neighborhood as it did following the
killing of the two Jewish settlers near Nablus. The Israeli
cabinet decided to expand Yitzhar to retaliate for their killing.
</P>
<P>
In a sign pointing to the rising tension, a Palestinian youth
was kidnapped and beaten by several settlers in Yitzhar Friday
before rescued by Israeli soldiers, Israel Radio reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
