<HEADLINE> Grand Jury Term Extended to Hear Tripp Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The term of a Howard County
grand jury in Maryland, that is considering possible wiretapping
violations by Linda Tripp will be extended indefinitely, a
prosecutor said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jurors have met twice monthly since March and took up the Tripp
question earlier this month. They had been scheduled to adjourn
September 17 after two more sessions.
</P>
<P>
But prosecutor Stephen Montanarelli's request for an extension
was granted Thursday by Circuit Judge James B. Dudley, said Howard
County State's Attorney Marna McLendon.
</P>
<P>
"We're not finished," The Associated Press quoted Montanarelli
as saying. "We've got a job to do and I'm going to do it. I was
handed this investigation.... I didn't ask for it."
</P>
<P>
At issue is whether Mrs. Tripp, who lives in Howard County,
broke Maryland law by secretly taping telephone conversations with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
The tapes triggered an investigation by Special Prosecutor
Kenneth Starr, and led to President Bill Clinton's public
admission Monday that he had an improper relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
Recording a telephone conversation in Maryland without the
other person's consent is a felony punishable by up to five years
in prison and fine of up to 10,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
But prosecutors must prove that someone accused of taping a
call without permission knew it was illegal. Tripp's lawyers have
maintained that their client wasn't aware of the law when she was
taping the conversations.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Murtha, an attorney for Tripp, said his client has not
been asked to appear before the jury and was "highly disappointed"
to hear of the extension.
</P>
<P>
"I still think, and we all believe, that this is a politically
motivated investigation," he said. "We believe it would be
appropriate just to close the investigation and allow Linda to get
on with her life." 
</P>
</TEXT>
