<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Commodity transport movement in Algeria's largest
port of Algiers registered a remarkable decline of 11.04 percent
in July 1998, as compared to the corresponding period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the latest bulletin of the Algiers Port Administration,
the Algerian news agency reported that the total tonnage of
commodity dealings last July amounted to 454,481 tonnes as compared
to 510,906 tonnes in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The cotton plantations in Syria have been seriously
damaged by the recent heat wave which swept through the country ,
particularly that it coincided with the growth of the cotton buds.
</P>
<P>
Friday's Arabic daily Al Hayat quoted Syrian agricultural
sources as saying that the average damage was some 23 percent of
the planned production by the Ministry of Agriculture. As a
matter of fact, the percentage of damages vary in regard to the
dates of cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Last year Syria produced more than 1 million tonnes of cotton.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Goweili
has disclosed that Egypt is currently producing 50 percent of its
needs of wheat, and is importing the rest in cash in conformity
with its own terms.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar held in the Cairo university Wednesday,
the Minister said that Egypt in 1982 was producing one fifth of
its bread, with the rest coming from donor countries on their own
terms. By then, he said, the wheat reserves were not even
sufficient for a week.
</P>
<P>
But the situation has greatly improved through the economic
reform policies. Now Egypt's foreign exchange reserves at the
central bank can cover Egypt's imports for 18 months, a fact that
is unprecedented in Egypt's recent history.
</P>
<P>
He said that Egypt imported 500,000 tonnes of wheat last year,
and would import this year only 197,000 tonnes. He said Egypt's
objective is to obtain 75 percent of self sufficiency for the
wheat consumption.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Dubai Municipality has decided to establish a
new gold market in the city next next year.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources here said that an appropriate site is
being considered so as to start preparing the designs that will
portray the distinct characteristics of the existing gold market,
presently located in one of Dubai's old districts.
</P>
<P>
The sources add that the new market will have an information
center linked with the various world stock exchanges, to be
abreast with gold and other precious metal dealings in world
markets.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the center will make studies on market trends and
effects of the diverse developments in world gold trading. The
Dubai gold market will also embrace units for gold designs with a
view to promoting the export of golden jewellery.
</P>
<P>
Last year Dubai exported more than 52 tonnes of golden jewellery,
and there is a growing demand on the part of regional markets in
Egypt, Pakistan and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Dubai is one of the biggest gold markets in the world in terms
of gold import which exceeded 600 tonnes last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
