<HEADLINE> U.S. Senator Warns Against Extending Deadlock in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Urging efforts to advance the
Mideast peace process, a U.S. senator warned here Friday of the
danger in the Middle East if the process continues to be
deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after meeting with Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi, Chuck Hagel, chairman of U.S. Senate's
International Economic Policy Subcommittee, called for joint
efforts by all parties concerned to salvage the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hagel arrived here in the day to continue his Mideast tour,
which has taken him to the Palestinian self-rule areas, Israel and
Egypt. He will also visit Syria and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is on a fact-finding mission aimed at getting
to know how the people in the region are viewing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I believe if we understand each other, the policy makers in
the U.S. Congress are able to make a practical decision," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stalled since
March last year after Israel began the construction of a Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as
the capital of a future independent state.
</P>
<P>
The talks are currently stuck over the overdue Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The peace negotiations between Israel and its two neighbors
Lebanon and Syria has been suspended in early 1996 due to the
disputes over the future of the Golan Heights that Israel captured
from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. senator underscored the importance of Lebanon in the
peace process, saying that it is a critical part and an effective
member in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a border strip in south Lebanon to
allegedly protect its northern areas from cross-border attacks by
the Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Israel has expressed willingness to pull out its troops from
South Lebanon unilaterally, provided the Lebanese governmnet
negotiates security arrangments with it. But Lebanon, backed by
its powerful ally Syria, has rejected the demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
