<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghanistan Raps at U.S. Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan on Friday
lashed out at Thursday's U.S. missile strikes, saying that such a
move "is against all norms and principles of international law"
and "sets a terrible example for the world."
</P>
<P>
The Afghan U.N. mission said in a faxed statement that "We
condemn in the strongest possible terms the United States missile
attack against the sovereignty of the Islamic Emirate of
Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. missile strike "is against all norms and principles of
international law," the statement said. "The U.S. has violated its
own long-held view that no individual, group or country should
take this kind of action into their own hands."
</P>
<P>
The United States on Thursday launched missile attacks on
Afghanistan and Sudan in retaliation to the August 7 twin bombings
in Kenya and Tanzania, in which U.S. officials alleged Osama bin
Laden, a Saudi-born millionaire, was involved.
</P>
<P>
In the case of bin Laden, the Afghan mission said in the
statement that the Asian nation "has made it clear by
communicating to various concerned parties that we were ready to
discuss the matter -- provided the U.S. presents some kind of
evidence."
</P>
<P>
But "these communications were completely ignored," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement described the U.S. request of the
millionaire's extradition as "untrue," saying "the United States
has yet to officially request that we hand bin Laden over to
them." Washington has so far failed to provide Kabul with
evidence which Afghanistan said is legally essential to the
extradition of the U.S.-claimed suspect, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement said Kabul will "limit bin Laden's
capacity to carry out subversive actions or propagandize against
any country from Afghan soil."
</P>
<P>
The statement said that 30 Afghan civilians were killed and 23
others were injured in the wake of the U.S. missile attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
