<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Vows to Fight Organized Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz vowed Friday to launch tougher crackdown on organized
crimes in the country, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"We are giving all kinds of material and moral support to the
security forces to combat organized crimes," Yilmaz told
reporters in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the government is determined to fight all kinds
of illegal activities."
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz made the statement at a time when the Turkish judicial
authorities are consulting with the French government about the
extradition of Turkey's notorious mafia boss Alaattin Cakici.
</P>
<P>
Cakici, 45, was arrested by the Turkish agents and French
police in Nice, France, on Monday, along with his lover and
bodyguard
</P>
<P>
Cakici, who has been wanted by the police for several criminal
charges, was the third Turkish mafia boss arrested in the past
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Kursat Yilmaz and Sedat Peker, two other mafia heads, were
arrested in Bulgaria and Istanbul respectively.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's organized crimes have been on rise in recent years,
causing serious social troubles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
