<HEADLINE> Tanzania Advocates Resolving Congo (K) Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa said Friday that the current conflict in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) should be resolved through
peaceful means instead of military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who is on a visit in Norway, callezd on countries in
Africa to be wary of being used as springboards to destabilize
other countries.
</P>
<P>
During separate official talks held in Oslo Friday with
Norwegian Prime Minister Kjell Magne Bondevik and Chairman of the
Parliamentary Standing Committee on Foreign Relations, Haakon
Blankenborg, Mkapa said any attempt by external forces to
intervene militarily in the conflict of the DRC will only
compound the already volatile situation in the country rather
that controlling it.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said the Committee of Four Countries established by a
special summit held in Zimbabwe a fortnight ago should be allowed
to promote a ceasefire between the rebels and the government of-
DRC, according to a press release issued by Geoffrey Nkurlu, the
press secretary to the Tanzanian president.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Four Countries should relentlessly endevour
to bring the warring parties to a negotiation table wqth an
objective of resolving the conflict through political settlement,
said Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, media reports said Zambia, Namibia and Zimbabwe have
joined the war in DRC where rebels are fighting the government of
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa have also met Norwegian businessmen and welcomed them
to invest in Tanzania, a country which has vast resources and
enjoys peace and tranquillity but lacks in capital and technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
