<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Minister on Multi-Racialism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior Singapore official
said that the current severe economic downturn has put Singapore
society under great stresses and the country's multi-racialism
demonstrates some merits and demerits.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Sikh community national day dinner at Singapore
Khalsa Club Saturday evening, Minister for Information and the
Arts and Second Minister for Trade and Industry George Yeo said,
"we do not know what other unhappy consequences will arise out of
this severe economic downturn" and "We can not assume that
Singapore society is invulnerable to such stresses."
</P>
<P>
Taking the topic on multi-racialism of which the Singapore
government is proud and in pursuit, the minister said, "our
multi-racialism is both a strength and a weakness."
</P>
<P>
"It is a strength because the different ethnic groups link us
to different parts of the world," he said, "without this
diversity Singapore cannot be a cosmopolitan entrepot and an
international financial center."
</P>
<P>
"However, our multi-racialism also means that we do not always
react in the same way to external events and foreign pressures,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In response to the hope expressed by a few Singaporeans that
the different races in Singapore will one day meld together into
a kind of local Singapore community, the minister said "this is
unlikely to happen because the races in Singapore have very
different historical memories."
</P>
<P>
"We have different gods, different patron saints and different
heroes." he said, adding "our religions are not going to fuse into
one and the rituals governing birth, marriage and death will
always remain different."
</P>
<P>
Calling for being "realistic and practical", George Yeo said
"in managing the complexities of multi-racialism in Singapore, we
should try to maximize our strengths and minimize our weaknesses."
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
