<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: No Sign of Relief Yet in China's Flooding Situation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Yangtze flooding has brought direct economic losses of at
least 200 billion yuan (24.1 billion U.S. dollars). More than 240
million people have been affected by the disaster.
</P>
<P>
And statistics show that more than 8.5 million people, or a
quarter of the total population in Heilongjiang Province, have
been affected by this year's devastating floods, with agricultural
losses of 14 billion yuan (1.69 billion U.S. dollars). Water has
destroyed 3.1 million hectares of farmland in 52 counties and
cities, damaged 1.44 million houses, killed 14,000 livestock, and
swamped more than 1,400 oil wells at Daqing Oil Field, the largest
in China.
</P>
<P>
Floods aroused great concern from State leaders. President
Jiang Zemin has postponed his visits to Russia and Japan because
of the flooding.
</P>
<P>
And Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, made several phone calls again on Friday to
leaders in flood-ravaged Heilongjiang and the Minister of Water
Resources in recent days, inquiring about the situation of major
Chinese rivers.
</P>
<P>
As the weather gets colder in northeast China, Li urged Party
and governments at all levels to pay even more attention to the
health of People's Liberation Army soldiers combating the
floods. He also called for adequate relief materials to be sent to
Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), visited
flood-stricken areas in central China's Hebei Province on Friday,
conveying cordial regards to flood-fighters there and urging them
to maintain high vigilance, overcome fatigue, and battle against
the flooding until a final victory is achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
