<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: No Sign of Relief Yet in China's Flooding Situation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The floods are still flowing at
a high-water level today in China, a sign of continuing difficulty
in the anti-disaster effort.
</P>
<P>
The third flood crest on the Songhua River today passed through
Harbin, a major heavy-industrial city in China's northernmost
province of Heilongjiang, with the water level climbing to 120.89
meters, 0.84 meters higher than the historic high, while the water
flow rate reaching 17,300 cubic meters per second by 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The water level of the city has not yet lowered much, according
to evening reports from China Central Television
(CCTV). Authorities attributed this to poor distribution on the
river section, noting that the width there ranges from 1-to-10 km,
which adds difficulties for the flow of the floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
"It is at a crucial moment to counter the flooding," said an
on-the-spot water control expert. A total of 400,000 soldiers and
civilians are safeguarding the city.
</P>
<P>
The sixth flood crest on the Yangtze River has reached Jiujiang
in east China's Jiangxi Province. It will have passed through
Jiujiang by Sunday afternoon. The water level at the city stood at
22.46 m at 2 p.m. today, 0.04 m more than Friday's level,
according to the latest information from the State Flood Control
and Drought Relief Headquarters (SFCDRH).
</P>
<P>
More than 300,000 troops of the People's Liberation Army and
armed police are working together with local residents to defend
the major embankments of the city.
</P>
<P>
Floodwaters dropped an insignificant 0.04-to-0.09 m today on
the section from Shashi to Hankou and at Dongting Lake on the
middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze. Water levels on the upper
reaches and the downstream section from Hankou, however, are still
rising.
</P>
<P>
Water levels at Chongqing, Shashi, Lianhuatang, Luoshan,
Hankou, and Chenglingji along the Yangtze stood at 180, 43.9,
35.7, 34.86, 29.32 m, the SFCDRH said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: No Sign of Relief Yet in China's Flood Situation (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The SFCDRH is sending more materials to flood-ravaged areas
along the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze, Nenjiang and
Songhua rivers. By Wednesday, the headquarters had sent 200
million yuan (24.1 million U.S. dollars) worth of goods to the
areas.
</P>
<P>
The Heilongjiang provincial civil affairs department has sent
eight working teams to help flood victims in the 10 hardest-hit
counties and cities. It has also provided 10 million yuan (1.2
million U.S. dollars) of relief funds, 17,000 cotton quilts and
900 tents to Qiqihar, the worst-hit industrial center, and Daqing
Oil Field.
</P>
<P>
Domestic and foreign donations sent to the Ministry of Civil
Affairs and its sub-departments across the country have surpassed
1.06 billion yuan (130 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A large benefit performance hosted by the ministries of Culture
and Civil Affairs Friday evening in the Great Hall of the People
raised nearly 1.1 billion yuan (133 million U.S. dollars) for
China's flood victims.
</P>
<P>
CPPCC Members have also opened their purses to provide funds
for flood victims in recent days, with seven non-governmental
entrepreneur members donating more than 30 million yuan (3.6
million U.S. dollars) of relief funds and materials, a number of
celebrated painters and calligraphers who are members selling 26
new works for charity, and members in Hong Kong providing 18
million Hong Kong dollars of relief funds.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs has pledged that every penny of
the relief funds will be used for the country's flood victims,
whose total number exceeds 240 million.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Health Zhang Wenkang said that the epidemic control
situation in China's flood-stricken areas is stable but infectious
diseases such as snail fever are threatening.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, about 400 cases of snail fever have been reported
to the ministry from Hubei, Hunan, Jiangxi, Heilongjiang, Anhui,
Jiangsu and Jilin provinces and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region, the areas which have suffered the most from the
floods. But experts have expected more cases in the near future
since snail fever has a fairly long latent period of 40 days.
</P>
<P>
The health minister acknowledged that the incidence of
intestinal epidemic diseases, dysentery, hepatitis and colds has
increased from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The major problem for epidemic control in the flood-stricken
areas is a shortage of funds and medicine, adding that the problem
could become worse in the next three months, usually the peak
period for the spread of epidemics in China, Zhang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
