<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, Sudan Call for Arab's Unity Against U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Sudan Saturday called
for an Arab solidarity to confront "the U.S.-imperialist
aggression."
</P>
<P>
The call was made in a meeting between Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz and the visiting Sudanese Foreign Minister
Mustafa Osman Ismail.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency said they discussed the U.S. air strikes
on a Sudanese pharmaceutical factory on Thursday and Iraq's
suspension of cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the necessity for Arab solidarity to face up to
the "U.S.-imperialist aggression targeting the Arab nation,
mainly the continued military aggression on Iraq, Sudan and other
unjust embargoes imposed for vicious political goals," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz denounced the U.S. move in Sudan together with the
previous military attacks on Iraq and Libya, saying they "have
turned the U.S. into an international criminal committing
terrorist acts in a flagrant and immoral manner."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night, the United States launched air strikes on
what they termed as "terrorist-related" bases in Afghanistan and
Sudan believed to have been behind the bombings of two
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
In the twin bombings on August 7, over 250 people were killed,
including 12 Americans, and more than 5,000 others wounded.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese minister, who arrived in Baghdad on Friday
afternoon, reiterated his country's support for the Iraqi people
and called for lifting the unjust sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Iraqi government announced suspension
of cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission for disarming
Iraq (UNSCOM) and the International Atomic Energy Agency,
complaining that UNSCOM is pro-U.S. and attempting to prolong the
sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. sanctions on Iraq following its 1990
invasion of Kuwait can not be lifted unless UNSCOM verifies that
it is free of chemical and biological weapons and long-range
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been insisting that the Security Council must consider
its legitimate demands by lifting the sanctions immediately,
otherwise, its decision to suspend cooperation with UNSCOM will
not change.
</P>
<P>
In a news conference held on Friday evening, Ismail described
as "savage" the U.S. aggression against his country, calling on
Arab governments to denounce it.
</P>
<P>
Sudan was one of the Arab states that sided with Iraq during
the 1991 Gulf War, and is branded by the U.S. as one of the
countries that sponsor terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Victims in Jiujiang Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Flood victims in Jiujiang city
in Jiangxi Province, east China, are returning to their homes
after being forced to flee by floodwaters on China's longest
river, the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
Huang Jianxin, owner of a small shop 100 meters from the
city's levees, said that traffic and the supply of drinking water
in the city have been resumed. However, the normal supply of
electricity has not been restored, he said.
</P>
<P>
Huang's shop has been reopened for business. His house,
submerged by floodwaters from the Yangtze, had been cleaned
thoroughly before his return.
</P>
<P>
Shen Xiujun, Huang's next-door neighbor, said that she went
back to her home with her mother and sister Friday and disinfected
her house with bleach provided by local health departments.
</P>
<P>
Shen said that many residents have returned home from their
temporary shelters. She said that one of the most urgent jobs is
clearing away layers of mud outside the house and taking
precautions against diseases after the floodwater subsides.
</P>
<P>
The Sanjiaoxian Flyover on the Jiujiang-Ruichang Highway, which
was forced to shut for 11 days, is now open to traffic.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, an area of 9 square kilometers in
the western part of Jiujiang was swept by floodwaters on August 7,
1998, when the city's levees were breached.
</P>
<P>
About 71,000 local residents were evacuated to safety. And the
city government located 100 more pumps in urban areas to remove
floodwaters day and night.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
