<HEADLINE> Lebanese Civilian Wounded in Israeli Shelling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A young Lebanese civilian was
wounded Saturday afternoon during an Israeli shelling on villages
in south Lebanon, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Samir Youssef Hamoud, 20, was wounded by shrapnel of Israeli
shells fired to the village of Arab Salim in the Iqlim al Tuffah
area facing the Israeli occupied zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, he was transferred to the hospital in
the nearby city of Nabatieh for treatment, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
He was the second injured by Israeli bombardment in less than
two days.
</P>
<P>
Since Friday, Israeli artillery troops have been pounding the
villages suspected to host an operation base for Lebanese
guerrillas after two Israelis were killed by a roadside bomb in
the south.
</P>
<P>
A 70-year-old Lebanese civilian, also from the village of Arab
Salim, was wounded Friday.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen Lebanese civilians have been killed and 73 others
wounded so far this year in clashes between Lebanese guerrillas
and Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon in 1985 to protect its north from cross-border
attack by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting
against Israel's occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
