<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabila, Mugabe Stay Away From Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Embattled Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC) President Laurent Kabila and his
Zimbabwean ally Robert Mugabe failed to turn up for peace talks
in Pretoria Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and his Rwandan counterpart,
Pasteur Bizimungu arrived at Waterkloof air base outside Pretoria
shortly before lunch, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's talks were aimed at securing a cease-fire in Congo
(K) and preventing an unprecedented war in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
Kabila sent his Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo in his place.
</P>
<P>
South African presidential aide Parks Mankahlana said Kabila
was resting on the advice of his doctor.
</P>
<P>
On Mugabe's failure to turn up, Mankahlana said South African
President Nelson Mandela had asked Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano to persuade the Zimbabwean leader to join Saturday's
meeting and Sunday's 14-member Southern African Development
Community (SADC) summit in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
He said South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki would also
try and convince Mugabe to attend.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe's troops appeared to have come under fire in Congo
Saturday, with rebels claiming that two jet fighters had been
shot down. But the Zimbabwean government denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Mugabe and Mandela have been strained over
the chairmanship of SADC's organ on politics, defense and
security.
</P>
<P>
Tension between the two men further intensified when Mugabe
headed a separate initiative in Congo and eventually called for
military intervention as opposed to Mandela's call for a peaceful
resolution.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is chairman of the SADC.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos, whose troops are
also backing Kabila in Congo, would not attend Sunday's summit
for medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
He would also send a representative, Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
All other SADC leaders would be present. It was hoped that
Saturday's talks between the Ugandans, Rwandans and Congolese
would work out a basis for putting a process in motion to
establish a government of national unity in the DRC and find
agreement on resolving the problem of the DRC through peaceful
means.
</P>
<P>
It was hoped Saturday's meeting would produce a proposal for
peace that would be tabled at Sunday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Mankahlana declined to comment on whether South Africa
expected a cease-fire to be conditional on the complete
withdrawal of foreign troops from Congo.
</P>
<P>
On whether Uganda and Rwanda, who are not members of the SADC,
would be observers at Sunday's meeting, he said: "We'll have to
find a way of allowing them to have a good sense of what is
happening, because they are key players in the conflict."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
