<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Drug Use Among the Young up in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- More young people in the
United States used illicit drugs last year, according to a survey
publicized by the government Friday.
</P>
<P>
Among those between the ages of 12-17 who were surveyed, 11.4
percent reported using some drugs within the past month, compared
with 9 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 9.4 percent of this group used marijuana, up from
7.1 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The annual National Household Survey on Drug Abuse reported
that the number of this group using heroin remained steady last
year, with only 0.2 percent stating they had used heroin within
the past month, the same figure as in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Marijuana is popular because many teens don't see it as
dangerous, said Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala.
</P>
<P>
Parents need to inform their children that marijuana is
dangerous -- that it can impair learning and memory, Shalala
said. They must also be more aware of the attitude they send to
their children about drugs.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted last year by interviews with 24,500
people in their homes.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicated an estimated 14 million people used drugs
last year, about 6.4 percent of the population. The overall drug
use rate in 1996 was 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Drug use among adults has been stable for years. Last year's
figure is slightly more than half the peak year in 1979, when
there were 25 million users. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
