<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Peace Talks Vital in Averting Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A regional bloodbath seemed imminent following reports that
Zimbabwean and Angolan troops have arrived in the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC) to support President Laurent Kabila
against rebels, whom Kabila claimed are backed by Rwanda and
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Friday, Rwandan ambassador to South Africa said his
country was ready for full-blown war with the DRC if Zimbabwe and
Namibia failed to immediately recall troops allegedly sent to the
DRC.
</P>
<P>
He said Rwandan troops were ready to go into the DRC to
protect "Rwanda's vital interest in eastern Congo".
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan government said Friday it reserved the right to
get involved in a conflict in the DRC" in whatever manner it
deems appropriate" and condemned some members of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC), led by Zimbabwe, for their
call for military aid to Kabila.
</P>
<P>
South African officials were locked in a planning session
Friday night to ensure everything was in place for the Saturday
meeting, which South Africa hopes will ensure a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will see Kabila sit down with his
allies-turned-foes, Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu and
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni, with Mandela and South African
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki acting as brokers.
</P>
<P>
It is not yet clear whether representatives of the rebel
forces will be present and whether Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe, a supporter of military intervention in the DRC, will
attend.
</P>
<P>
The 14-nation SADC, a regional economic bloc, is split on the
approach to resolve the crisis in the DRC, where Tutsi-led
rebellion since the beginning of the month had wrecked havoc and
rebels had advanced close to the capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and Zambia called for military
intervention to help Kabila to quell the revolt, and South
Africa, Botswana and Mozambique preferred a peaceful, long-term
political solution.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who chairs the SADC's suspended organ on defense and
security, rebuked Mandela publicly in a rare incidence earlier
this week, telling him not to interfere with SADC members who
wished to assist Kabila militarily.
</P>
<P>
The Saturday talks will be followed on Sunday by a special
summit of the SADC, currently chaired by Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's spokesman said plans were "far advanced" and there
was an agreement in principle from all the parties involved to
attend the talks.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba is expected to attend the
Sunday summit, when he would brief his SADC colleagues on the
meeting he had with Rwandan Vice-President Paul Kagame Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks is the culmination of two weeks of South
African diplomacy aimed at bringing a peaceful resolution to the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo and Defense Minister Joe Modise
shuttled between South Africa, Kabila's stronghold in Lubumbashi
and the capitals of Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and Mbeki also made numerous telephone calls to Kabila
and other regional leaders, including former Tanzanian President
Julius Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has repeatedly said it does not believe in any
military solution to the Congo crisis.
</P>
<P>
It said the only way out would be to secure a meeting between
the rebels and the Kabila government, which would lead to the
Congolese people hammering out a broad-based democratic order for
their own country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
