<HEADLINE> China's Anhui Strives to Improve Farmland Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province will
spend 2.92 billion yuan (about 351 million U.S. dollars) in three
years to improve the quality of low-yield farmland.
</P>
<P>
Anhui currently has more than 2.66 million hectares of medium-
and low-yield farmland. The planned funds can help improve the
quality of 446,000 hectares, a provincial agricultural official
said.
</P>
<P>
Anhui has formulated a plan to improve 666,000 hectares of
medium- and low-yield farmland for the five years between 1996 and
2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
Anhui first launched an effort to improve farmland quality in
1988, with investment for that purpose totaling more than 3.1
billion yuan. So far, Anhui has improved the quality of more than
900,000 hectares of medium- and low-yield farmland, raising the
annual output of agricultural produce by 2.83 billion kilograms.
 
