<HEADLINE> Manila May Provide Security to Former Army Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
ready to provide security to former Army Chief of Staff Fabian Ver
in case there is a threat to his life once he returns to the
Philippines, Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"If there are genuine safety concerns, like any citizen, and if
the government believes that those safety concerns are valid, we
can provide the adequate protection that is required," Barican
told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
But before providing security men to Ver, Barican said, the
authorities will have to first assess the actual extent of the
risk on Ver's life as well as the length of time required to
address such a threat.
</P>
<P>
Barican also said that granting immunity to the former army
chief in connection with the Aquino-Galman double murder case is
not being considered.
</P>
<P>
Ver served as army chief of staff of president Ferdinand
Marcos, and is widely suspected to be one of the masterminds
behind the assassination of former Senator Benigno Aquino Jr. on
August 21, 1983. Ver fled overseas when Marcos was toppled in
February 1986.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Ver is recovering from a lung disease, and
hopes to be back in Manila "in two to three months."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, President Joseph Estrada gave the go-ahead
to Ver's return to the Philippines on the ground that he is no
longer considered a national security threat.
</P>
<P>
Estrada expressed hope that Ver would finally shed on the
assassination of former Senator Aquino, but he has to face all
criminal charges pending in court against him.
</P>
<P>
Ver is facing criminal charges as an accomplice in the double
murder case of Aquino and Rolando Galman, the former senator's
alleged hitman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
