<P>
Mandela has invited the presidents of Congo (K), Rwanda,
Uganda, Zimbabwe and Angola, the main players in the crisis, for
talks in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who ousted late dictator Mobutu Sese Seko in May
1997, accuses his former allies Rwanda and Uganda of invading in
support of the Tutsi-led rebels. Both deny the charge.
</P>
<P>
The crisis has split the Southern African Development
Community (SADC), with Mandela taking the lead for countries keen
to see a negotiated solution and Zimbabwe's president Robert
Mugabe favoring military assistance for Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said 600 Zimbabwean troops with four
fighter jets might have arrived in Kinshasa and 500 Angolan
soldiers have poured into the northern Cabinda enclave, moving
toward the border with Democratic Congo.
</P>
<P>
However, government sources in Harare said Zimbabwe will not
attend unless the other four countries -- Angola, Namibia,
Tanzania and Zambia -- are also present at the talks.
</P>
<P>
"A meaningful meeting will have to be one where all key
players are in participation," one government source told the
official paper of Zimbabwe "Daily Herald".
</P>
<P>
But Mandela had asked Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano to
try and persuade Mugabe to change his mind and make the summit
and Rwandan President Pasteur Bisimungu and Uganda's Yoweri
Museveni were already in South Africa for the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
