<HEADLINE> Estrada Backs Probe of Alleged Army Fund Anomalies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Saturday gave his full backing to the investigation being
conducted by Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado into alleged fund
irregularities in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with a local radio, Estrada said the Department
of National Defense should push through with such an investigation
in line with the administration's campaign against corruption.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said Friday that powerful military officers, including
some retired generals, are orchestrating coup rumors as "a
psychological war" tactic to discourage the government from
investigating fund irregularities in the armed force.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said that when he was still a senator and later, Vice
President, he had already received complaints concerning the
army's Retirement and Separation Benefits System (RSBS) as well as
the non-release of pension benefits of war veterans.
</P>
<P>
He said that Mercado had reported to him that one possible
anomaly is the surprise increase in the number of veterans
supposedly availing of RSBS benefits.
</P>
<P>
Mercado has been prying into the reported dissipation of funds
at the RSBS and the Philippine Veterans Administration Office.
</P>
<P>
"I am giving my all-out support behind Secretary Mercado
because even the surveys show that the people are fed up with
graft and corruption in government," Estrada said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
