<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40m Ethiopians Suffer From Iodine Deficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Health of
Ethiopia estimated that nearly 40 million people in the country
are suffering from iodine deficiency.
</P>
<P>
An official from the ministry, Mekonnen Admassu, was quoted by
the Ethiopian News Agency as saying Saturday that people living
in highland areas in particular are prone to iodine deficiency
mainly due to soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian highlands, called "Roof of Africa", cover the
western and central Ethiopia, two-thirds of the country with
average of between 2,500 and 3,000 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
Mekonnen said the iodine content in the soil and water as well
as the food the local people consume is very low.
</P>
<P>
"It is incumbent upon all salt producers to mix the salt they
supply to the market with iodine in order to address the
problem," the official said, adding that this is not often the
case at present.
</P>
<P>
He said the Ministry of Health and the United Nations
Children's Fund provide organized salt producers with the
machinery and chemical needed to iodize salt.
</P>
<P>
He said negotiations are underway with the Health Ministers
of Yemen and Kenya to facilitate the import of iodized salt into
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian imported iodized salt from Eritrea before the
outbreak of the border dispute between two countries in May, this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
