<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan-Egypt Flights Unaffected Despite U.S. Raid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The flights between the capitals
of Sudan and Egypt have not been disrupted by the U.S. strikes
against a Khartoum pharmaceutical plant Thursday night, the Middle
East News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
An EgyptAir returned home Friday morning from Khartoum,
touching down at Cairo airport with 161 passengers of different
nationalities on board.
</P>
<P>
Cairo airport control tower received a phone call from Khartoum
airport immediately after the U.S. strike notifying that it will
continue to receive flights from Cairo and that Sudan's air space
will remain open to air navigation.
</P>
<P>
EgyptAir's three Cairo-Khartoum regular weekly flights will
proceed as usual, an official at the airport said.
</P>
<P>
In its first response to Thursday's U.S. air strikes on alleged
terrorist-associated facilities in Sudan and Afghanistan, Egypt
called on the United Nations to host a world summit on combating
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
It urged the U.N. Security Council to take appropriate measures
in line with the U.N. Charter to fight and root out terrorism and
bring those responsible to justice.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. fired cruise missiles Thursday night at a
pharmaceutical factory near Khartoum in what it claimed
retaliation for bombings August 7 at its embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has accused Sudan of sponsoring international
terrorism and claimed that the factory was manufacturing chemical
weapons agents that could be used by Islamic militants to launch
new attacks against U.S. targets.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Sudan, the two Nile neighbors, have be in disputes
over border and other hanging issues, and traded accusations of
harboring militants against each other. There appeared to be a
tentative thaw in relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
