<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earlist Poems Still Popular in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Literary researchers have
discovered that a group of China's earliest poems are still quite
popular in mountainous regions in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The researchers visited the Heyang Mountain Area in
Zhangjiagang City and found that most villagers there love singing
poetry put to music in the form of folk songs.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 ancient poems have been collected totalling
250,000 characters. Most of the poems tell of local people's daily
lives and labor. Some recorded historical events.
</P>
<P>
The longest one has 8,458 lines, a love story. Another folk
song recording of wood-cutters harvesting bamboo was produced
nearly 2,500 years ago, believed to be one of the earliest poems.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
