<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, France to Cooperate Despite Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran and France on Saturday
voiced readiness to expand cooperation in all fields, despite of
their differences over some issues.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally there are some differences between Iran and France
in some fields," Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said at a
joint press conference with his visiting French counterpart Hubert
Vedrine after their first round of talks.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the two countries share similar views over
various regional and international issues.
</P>
<P>
Terming his talks with Vedrine as "friendly and fruitful," he
said that Tehran was ready to expand bilateral relations with
Paris in all fields based on mutual benefits.
</P>
<P>
"The independence of the two governments' foreign policies
paved the grounds for expansion of Tehran-Paris cooperation,
particularly in the fields of oil and gas industries," Kharrazi
noted.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine, who arrived here Friday night for a two-day official
visit, said that his first round of talks with Kharrazi was
focused on bilateral relations, particularly the prospect of
mutual cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During his stay he and Iranian officials would discuss "every
issue and every point" of concern for the two sides, such as the
British writer Salman Rushdie, human rights and weapons of mass
destruction, Vedrine said.
</P>
<P>
Rushdie, who was accused of blasphemy to Islam for his novel
the "Satanic Verses," was condemned to death by Iran's late
spiritual leader Ayatollah khomeini.
</P>
<P>
"France is interested at holding talks with Iran over any
issue and will continue dialogue with Iran in all fields," said
the French minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
