<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8.5 million People in Heilongjiang Province Affected by Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The flood crest on the Songhua
River in northeast China passed through this capital of China's
northernmost province of Heilongjiang today.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Harbin climbed to 120.89 meters by 2
p.m. today, 0.84 meters higher than the historic high at a flow
rate of 17,300 cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.5 million flood victims in Heilongjiang have been
evacuated to safety, according to a local civil affairs official.
</P>
<P>
The provincial civil affairs department has sent eight working
teams to help flood victims in the 10 hardest-hit counties and
cities. It has also provided 10 million yuan (1.2 million US
dollars) of relief funds, 17,000 cotton quilts and 900 tents to
Qiqihar, the worst-hit industrial center, and Daqing Oil Field,
the largest of its kind in China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the provincial civil affairs department shows
that more than 8.5 million people, or a quarter of the total
population in Heilongjiang, have been affected by this year's
devastating floods, with agricultural losses of 14 billion yuan
(1.69 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Floods have destroyed 3.1 million hectares of farmland in 52
counties and cities, damaged 1.44 million houses and killed 14,000
livestock.
</P>
<P>
Provincial government has distributed 30 million yuan (3.6
million US dollars) of relief funds to flood victims. It received
an additional 12 million yuan (1.45 million US dollars) of relief
funds, 3.2 million yuan (386,000 US dollars) in relief materials,
200,000 articles of clothing and 150,000 yuan in food and medicine
in recent days, according to the civil affairs official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
