<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lhasa Residents Living in More Spacious Apartments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Lhasa, capital of
southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region, now live in more
spacious apartments than people in many other Chinese
cities, according to the local construction department.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey showed that, by the end of June, the average
housing space for Lhasa residents had reached 15.24 square meters,
one of the largest among 35 large and medium-sized cities across
the country.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, the per capita living space in Lhasa was merely 3.82
square meters, and local residents often complained about their
poor housing facilities.
</P>
<P>
During the past two decades since China launched its reform and
opening-up drive, nearly 20 major housing projects have been
completed in Lhasa. In 1997 alone, the city built new apartments
with a total floor space of 280,000 square meters and renovated
nearly 300,000 square meters of old housing, offering a large and
comfortable home to several thousand local households.
</P>
<P>
As the housing system reform has been started nationwide, local
construction officials are expecting a sharp increase in the
purchase of private apartments in the coming months, which they
believe will help further improve the housing conditions in
Lhasa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
