<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Architects, Archeologists Try to Save Leaning Tower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists and architects in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province have been busy working on a
1,000-year-old leaning tower, trying to return it to its original
place.
</P>
<P>
The 23-meter-tall brick tower, built during the Northern Song
Dynasty (960-1127), has been on a county-level protection list
since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
According to local chronicles, the last renovation was done about
300 years ago. Since then, the tower began leaning northwards, with
the rate increasing during the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
The province has allocated special funds, and the provincial
historical relics protection department is fully responsible for
the necessary repairs, said an official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
