<BODY>
<HEADLINE> INLA Guerrillas Announce Ceasefire in Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Irish National Liberation
Army (INLA) guerrilla group on Saturday announced a ceasefire in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The Irish Republican Socialist Party, the political wing of the
INLA, announced in Belfast that the INLA ceasefire would begin at
noon on Saturday, according to BBC report.
</P>
<P>
"The Irish National Liberation Army has now shifted from the
position of defence and retaliation to the position of complete
ceasefire," the group said.
</P>
<P>
It said it believed that the conditions for armed struggle no
longer exist and units had been ordered to end "offensive actions"
to achieve their goal.
</P>
<P>
The INLA, formed in 1975 after a split with the mainstream
Irish Republican Army (IRA), is one of Northern Ireland's most
ruthless republican guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
Another splinter guerrilla group, the Real IRA, which was
responsible for the Omagh bombing a week ago, declared a ceasefire
on Wednesday. The bomb blast killed 28 people and injured more than
200.
</P>
<P>
The Omagh bombing has generated a wave of revulsion in both
Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic. The INLA's statement left
only one Republican guerrilla group -- the Continuity IRA -- still
wedded to violence in the pursuit of a united Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
