<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Chad, Niger Meet on Sub-regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Defense and foreign ministers of
Nigeria, Chad and the Niger Republic Friday met in Nigerian
capital Abuja to discuss security problems on their common
border.
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting were the Nigerian Chief of Defense
Staff, Air Vice-Marshal Al-Amin Daggash, Chadian Minister of
Defense Oumar Kedgelani and Maman Sidikou, the Nigerien Minister
of Foreign Affairs and African Integration.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is coming on heel of a mini-summit attended by
leaders of the three countries on regional issues on August 12.
</P>
<P>
In a communique signed at the end of their meeting the leaders
expressed concern over the threat to peace, security and
stability posed by the activities of rebels, bandits and other
undesirable elements in the Lake Chad area.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian host Daggash was quoted by media reports as
saying at Friday's meeting that there is the need to thoroughly
appraise the problems and the true situation on the ground in all
their dimensions.
</P>
<P>
"It is only through such clear-headed analysis that we can
come out with action-oriented, practical and forward-looking
recommendations that would not only lend themselves to effective
implementation but also stand the test of time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Daggash urged the three governments to show their political
will and allow necessary resources for the implementation of
whatever plan that was made.
</P>
<P>
Chadian Defense Minister expressed his optimism on the
region's capacity to find solutions to its problems.
</P>
<P>
If Nigeria can effectively solve the problems of other
countries on the continent, there shouldn't be any force to
prevent it from doing the same to itself and its neighbors, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Nigerien Foreign Minister Maman Sidikou reportedly applauded
the decision to eliminate banditry and other crimes in the
sub-region, observing that the three governments were duty bound
to ensure peace in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
