<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Disagrees With U.S. Retaliatory Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Saturday voiced
its disagreement with the way the United States executed its
unilateral retaliatory action against Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim said in
Cyberjaya, about 50 kilometers from here, that such actions must
be taken via proper channels through the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"Although they claim their actions are justified, it can
jeopardize procedures of international relations. When one country
decides unilaterally to attack another country which has committed
an offense, what is the role of world bodies such as the U.N.
which should be the forum to discuss such matters to reach a
consensus," Anwar told reporters after visiting the Multimedia
University project site in Cyberjaya.
</P>
<P>
The United States launched a cruise missile attack on
Afghanistan and Sudan Thursday which were alleged to be involved
in the August 7 bombings of the U.S. embassy buildings in Kenya
and Tanzania. Afghanistan and Sudan had since denied any
involvement in the bombings.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that in an effort to defend its integrity or
sovereignty, one country should not be allowed to attack another
but instead must go through proper channels such as international
forums.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to Malaysia's national news agency
Bernama, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said Saturday
at Ketereh in the northeastern state of Kelantan that the
launching of missile strikes on innocent people by a Western
nation seeking to avenge the death of its people is "an act of
cowardice."
</P>
<P>
Such tyranny was inflicted on nations that had not declared war
against the Western nation, Mahathir said without naming any
nation, but obviously he was referring the to the United States
which launched missile strikes against alleged terrorist targets
in Afghanistan and Sudan in retaliation for the bombing of the
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania earlier, Bernama said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Team Ends Inspection in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A team of the Federation of
International Football Association (FIFA) Friday ended its
one-week inspection of the facilities for the 1999 World Youth
Championship dubbed Nigeria '99.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Abuja with the Nigerian Chief of General Staff,
Rear Admiral Mike Akhigbe, FIFA Vice-President Jack Warner said
the team was extremely impressed with the quality of work taking
place at the seven stadiums visited.
</P>
<P>
The seven stadiums are located in Bauchi, Port Harcourt,
Kano,Ibadan, Calabar, Kaduna and Lagos.
</P>
<P>
Warner, however, said the FIFA team had some degree of
discomfort regarding the hotel facilities, except those in Enugu
and Lagos.
</P>
<P>
"We are optimistic that the facilities (in the stadium) shall
all be completed on time and that these facilities shall be
second to none," Warner said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that about 500 football players were being expected
as the competition would be beamed to over 160 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
"It is against this backdrop that we are trying our utmost to
ensure that the hotel facilities are acceptable to athletes,
guests and the media," he said.
</P>
<P>
Responding, Akhigbe, who was speaking on behalf of the
Nigerian leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar, said the Nigerian
government has taken due note of the observations made by the
team and that the relevant bodies had been directed to address
these challenges to ensure a successful hosting of the
championship.
</P>
<P>
Akhigbe assured the FIFA team that Nigeria's political
transition program which is billed to usher in a civilian
government in May 1999 will not affect its hosting of the
championship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
