<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Teams to Perform Cataract Operations in Poor Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Four medical teams of
outstanding doctors will soon go to 10 counties in north China's
Shanxi Province, where health care conditions are poor, to perform
a series of cataract operations.
</P>
<P>
That is part of a nationwide effort -- Sight First China Action
-- aimed at helping cataract-afflicted blind people regain their sight.
</P>
<P>
This project, a joint venture launched last August by the
Ministry of Health, the China Disabled Persons Federation and
Lions Clubs International, will perform 1.75 million cataract
operations within the next five years throughout China.
</P>
<P>
A total of 250 medical teams will go to remote and
poverty-stricken areas during the course of this effort.
</P>
<P>
So far. some 348,000 operations have been performed, including
1,202 in Shanxi.
</P>
<P>
With 117,000 cataract patients living mostly in remote areas,
Shanxi plans to operates on 46,000 of them during the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
Cataracts are the cause of blindness for more than four million
Chinese, almost half the total number of blind people across the
country. Each year, about 400,000 new cases of blindness are
caused by cataracts.
</P>
<P>
However, only 2.1 million cataract operations and artificial
lens implants were performed between 1988 and 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
