<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibition on Rehabilitation Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong International
Exhibition on Rehabilitation 1998 with "a Brave New World" as its
theme was opened here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest of its kind in the Asia and Pacific region,
which is designed to promote public understanding and concern for
disabled persons as well as to enhance equal participation and
building a harmonious society for both the persons with or without
disability.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is divided into three main sections.
</P>
<P>
These include the Jockey Club Pavilion, containing an extensive
range of services supported by the Hong Kong Jockey Club; a public
education pavilion to promote public concern on disability; and a
pavilion consisting of more than 100 booths, mainly introducing
the salutary work of the government, non-governmental
organizations and the voluntary sector.
</P>
<P>
On display are rehabus, wheelchairs, specially-designed kitchen
and eating utensils, equipment to improve accessibility, personal
care materials, medical equipment for the chronically ill, toys
for disabled children as well as various kinds of products made by
disabled people.
</P>
<P>
Harry Fang, president of the event, said at the opening
ceremony that this rehabilitation and social services exhibition
is "intended to provide useful information and knowledge not only
to the well informed but to the public at large."
</P>
<P>
The event serves as a venue for the exchange of information on
rehabilitation technologies. The well-developed support facilities
 enable disabled persons to take care of themselves and lead an
independent life, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Arthur O'Reilly, president of the Rehabilitation
International, said, "The exhibition was a marvelous educational
opportunity for all."
</P>
<P>
The four-day-long exhibition is organized by the Joint Council
for the Physically and Mentally Disabled and supported by the
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and the
Hong Kong Jockey Club Charities Trust.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Jockey Club, founded in 1884 to organize all
racing activities in Hong Kong, is a non-profit organization,
annually donating about 1 billion HK dollars (128.21 million
U.S. dollars) to community and charitable projects through its
Charities Trust. 
</P>
</TEXT>
