<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PC Prices Tumble to New Low in U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A California-based personal
computer maker Friday began to sell its product for only 399
U.S. dollars, waging a new round of price-war among the PC makers.
</P>
<P>
PrecisionTec LLC introduced its Gazelle machine for sale over
the Internet through Egghead.com and other Web-site companies. The
lowest price does not include computer monitor, which usually
starts at about 150 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Micro Center, an Ohio-based chain of 13
computer stores, was the first to sell a 399-dollar computer under
the Power Spec label.
</P>
<P>
Personal computer prices, which tumbled below the 1,000 dollars
just 18 months ago, now are breaking through the 400-dollar price
mark.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts noted that low price does not mean the low
quality. They said that today's computers costing below 1,000
dollars are equal or greater in power than PCs costing 1,500
dollars and more just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes you don't need a Ferrari to drive 55 miles an hour
down the freeway," said John Torres, head of a California-based
Millennium, whose 499-dollar machine comes equipped with a
200-megahertz microprocessor from Integrated Device Technology, and
runs Microsoft's latest Windows 98 operating system.
</P>
<P>
The analysts said that the plunge in PC prices reflects
declining wholesale prices for computer parts, such as
microprocessors, memory chips and hard drives.
</P>
<P>
Because of the sharp drop, they estimated, nearly 50 percent of
U.S. families are expected to own a desktop PC by the end of 1998,
a significant increase from 45 percent at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, they also voiced their concern that the low-priced
computer trend had made it difficult for hardware-makers like
Intel to maintain their historically high profit margins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Shocked at U.S. Air Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B. J.
Habibie Saturday said he was shocked and worried when he received
news about the U.S. missile attacks in Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"I felt very sorry and very sad. But it was not an attack
against Islam," the president told reporters from the Middle East
during an interview at his presidential office here.
</P>
<P>
Habibie was quoted by Antara News Agency as saying the attacks
could not be against Islam, since the United States has good
relations with Muslim countries like Indonesia, which has the
biggest Muslim population in the world, and the Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
The president said that what the world, including Europe, the
United States and Japan, should do together is to declare war on
poverty, injustice and ignorance.
</P>
<P>
"I think the communities of the world, whatever their religion,
have to go hand-in-hand in declaring war against poverty,
injustice and ignorance," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Foreign Ministry on Friday expressed deep
concern over the implications of the bomb blasts at the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania but disapproved of any
intervention in and aggression against sovereign countries in
fighting terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
