<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Official Off to London for Talks With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmed left here for London Saturday to represent Pakistan
in the fourth round of talks with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Islamabad hopes for a better understanding of its security
concern vis-a-vis non-proliferation efforts including the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
Officials here confirmed Saturday that the Pak-U.S. talks will
start on August 25. However, it is not clear as to how long the
fourth round of talks will last.
</P>
<P>
A White House official said last Sunday that Washington
expected the London round of talks to be "decisive" in regard to
the "progress forward" in the discussions between Pakistan and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Islamabad maintains an open position on CTBT but emphasizes
that its vital security be considered deeply.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad made it clear last month that CTBT is not an anathema
for Pakistan, stressing that Islamabad's determination of the time
of acceding to CTBT depends on the protection of its security
concerns.
</P>
<P>
Since the third round of talks was held between the two
countries in Islamabad last month, Pakistan has shown its
commitment to the international non-proliferation efforts by
joining the discussions on a fissile material cut treaty in
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Washington, which started the diplomatic talks with both
Pakistan and India after their nuclear tests in May, has been
urging the two countries to join CTBT.
</P>
<P>
Last month, U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott told
reporters here that he was discussing some "very very tough
issues" with the Pakistani officials, with Washington trying to
"reconcile Islamabad's national interests with its
non-proliferation objectives."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Islamabad also calls for "a clear demonstration of
collective engagement on the part of the major powers in the
process of peace and security in south Asia which has to focus on
Kashmir." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
