<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Troops Deployed in Congo (K): Paper  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Angola, Namibia, Zambia and Tanzania agreed at a meeting of
defense ministers to render material or manpower assistance to
Congo as part of the southern African initiative to support its
government in its battle with the Tutsi-led rebels, the Daily
Herald, Zimbabwe's most influential newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The deployments are reported to have the limited aim of
preventing the rebels from seizing Kinshasa. Once the war becomes
unfavorable toward the rebels, it is expected that serious
negotiations will become possible, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The 14-member Southern African Development Community decided
to act swiftly in support of Congolese President Laurent Kabila
after rebels claimed they were 120 km away from Kinshasa. They
rebelled in eastern Congo on August 2 to oust President Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean troops, whose numbers could not be ascertained
Friday, were picked from different battalions around the country.
They left in groups from Manyame Air Base beginning Wednesday,

the paper said.
</P>
<P>
But reports reaching here said 500 Angolan soldiers have
poured into the northern Cabinda enclave, moving toward the
border with Democratic Congo and that 600 Zimbabwean troops with
four fighter jets have arrived in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's deployment in the DRC comes in the wake of
conflicting opinions of how to deal with the escalating crisis in
the DRC.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is trying to discourage SADC member states from
being militarily involved in DRC, a position which contradicts a
decision taken by the regional grouping's Ministers of Defense
meeting in harare this week.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela has now called an
emergency meeting of leaders from Uganda, Rwanda, the DRC and
Zimbabwe in Pretoria Saturday to discuss the DRC crisis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is to be followed by a full SADC summit at the
same venue.
</P>
<P>
However, Zimbabwe will not attend unless the other four
countries -- Angola, Nambia, Tanzania and Zambia -- are also
present, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Government sources Friday said Zimbabwe had wanted other
players in the DRC crisis including Namibia, Tanzania, Zambia and
Angola to participate.
</P>
<P>
"A meaningful meeting will have to be one where all key
players are in participatiKI$K+$.+.,Y.XZ2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
