<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: More American Teenagers Using Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A survey released Friday
showes that 11.4 percent of American teenagers used some illicit
drug in 1997, compared with 9 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The annual National Household Survey on Drug Abuse (NHSDA) was
conducted throughout last year by interviews with 24,500 people in
their homes, the NHSDA report said.
</P>
<P>
The drug of choice among the group (ages 12 to 17) was
marijuana, with 9.4 percent using it last year, remarkably
increasing from 7.1 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The most dangerous increase was the number of first-time heroin
users, which was at an all-time high in 1996, the last year for
which numbers were available. Preliminary numbers indicate 3.9
million teens used heroin for the first time in 1996, almost
doubled the 2.2 million who tried it in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts blamed the increase of first-time heroin users
among teens on the "relaxed attitude" to their parents.
</P>
<P>
Parents need to inform their children that marijuana is
dangerous -- that it can impair learning and memory, warned Health
and Human Services Setretary Donna Shalala.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, according to the survey, about 14 million people,
or 6.4 percent of the U.S. population, said they used drugs in
1997, compared 6.1 percent in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Steps Up Power Construction in Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, August 22 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region recently kicked off a two-billion-yuan project
to upgrade power grids in the region's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
In the next four months, Inner Mongolia will build and upgrade
20,000 kilometers of power transmission lines, construct and
enlarge 73 substations, and erect other auxiliary facilities.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates say that power construction in the
region's rural areas will give impetus to production of
manufactured goods with an added value totaling 700 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
This is just part of the region's efforts to build and improve
its infrastructure. To support this work, the regional government
has added an extra investment of four billion yuan mainly to
finance construction and upgrading of projects in six areas,
including power construction in rural areas, environmental
protection in urban areas, transportation and telecommunications,
housing, and grain depots, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
Yun Gongmin, vice-chairman of the regional government, said
Inner Mongolia's investment in fixed assets this year will exceed
its earlier budget by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia is set to achieve a ten percent economic growth
this year, two percent of which will be ensured by increasing
investment in fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has set up a leading group to
coordinate infrastructure construction, and a special group in
charge of the construction of grain depots and power grids in the
region's rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
