<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Economic Westward Movement (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- China's more-developed provinces
and municipalities in the east have launched a westward movement
to help boost economic growth in the central and western parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The east has been transferring funds, gifted people,
technology, industries and information to the less-developed
central and western areas at an unprecedented rate, economists say.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's economic and financial center, for example,
has launched more than 260 projects in the Tibet Autonomous
Region, Yunnan Province and the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
since last year.
</P>
<P>
More and more entrepreneurs in Guangdong Province, a showcase
of China's market economy reforms in the south, are moving their
manufacturing plants to the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region,
which neighbors Guangdong but is much less developed.
</P>
<P>
"The westward movement is a major trend of China's reforms and
opening-up program," Hu Angang, a noted economist of the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Just as the United States began to develop its western areas in
the 1860s, China has gradually become able to develop its vast
areas in the west, said Hu, who is renowned for his studies on
China's national conditions.
</P>
<P>
"After 20 years of market economy reforms, China has already
had a relatively strong economic power and overall national
strength, and its provinces and municipalities in the east have
developed an ability to bring along economic growth in the west,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The central and western areas, which account for 86 percent of
China's territory and 58 percent of the nation's population, have
rich natural resources, cheap labor forces, and huge market
potential. They have lagged behind the east in economic
development because of historical reasons and poor geographic
locations.
</P>
<P>
When China launched its reform and opening-up program in
the late 1970s, it issued many preferential policies to attract
overseas investment and technology to the coastal east.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Economic Westward Movement (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In recent years, however, the Chinese government has attached
increasing importance to spurring economic growth in the central
and western parts to narrow the disparity in overall economic
development. The measures adopted toward that end include the
introduction of a fiscal transfer payment beginning in 1995, the
direction of overseas investment and the move of much of the
textile industry to the central and western areas where cotton is
produced, and the launching of many poverty-relief projects in
central and western China, among others.
</P>
<P>
South China's Guangdong Province, for example, put aside 10
million yuan this year to aid enterprises that launch projects in
Guangxi. Last year alone, Guangdong signed for 60 cooperative
projects in Guangxi, with a total investment of 1.75 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the westward movement by enterprises in the
east has increasingly been driven by market forces, as they often
use their competitive edge in technology, funds, management and
brand names to merge with or take over firms in the less-developed
areas.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that Shanghai alone has invested 10
billion yuan in founding more than 1,000 enterprises in central
and western China. In many of the new firms, Shanghai has a
controlling stake.
</P>
<P>
Experts also say that the launching of many key projects in the
central and western areas has accelerated the westward movement of
industries and investment.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi's Qinzhou, which is on the Nanning-Kunming Railway, a
major line in the southwest, attracted 137 projects transferred
from Guangdong in the first half of this year, with investment
totaling more than 200 million yuan. The projects also created
nearly 20,000 job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has launched 56 cooperative projects in Chongqing,
which used to be part of southwestern Sichuan Province but was
made a municipality in 1997, with pledged investment hitting 350
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Just like Chinese investors from the east, overseas consortia
and companies have also showed their confidence in the development
projects of China's central and western areas.
</P>
<P>
In Yichang, where the giant Three Gorges Projects is being
built, paid-in overseas investment exceeded more than 100 million
U.S. dollars last year alone, about 4.8 times the 1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
Though overseas companies have continued to invest more in east
China, their investment in central and western China has
significantly outgrown that in the east.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the prevailing westward movement will make the
central and western parts of China a major growth area.
</P>
<P>
So long as the trend continues, the days for coordinated
economic development between the east and the west are not far
away, they say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
