<HEADLINE> Brief Latin American Cultural Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are news
briefs about cultural, arts and entertainment events which have
taken place over the past few days:
</P>
<P>
Panama holds Pollera Festival
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Festival of the Pollera is being held until
Saturday, in which the best polleras and shirts of the country
will be awarded prizes.
</P>
<P>
The pollera is a typical dress with which Panamanian women show
their beauty at the rhythm of the music, and is the product of an
anonymous art that has been created and developed in the warmth of
rural households.
</P>
<P>
Georgia Children Present Typical Dances of Their Country
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- A group of 35 children, members of the Georgia
National Ballet School, will present here Saturday and next
Saturday, the program "Virtuous Children of the Caucasus."
</P>
<P>
The local press says that the group presents a show that
rescues the most essential aspects of their culture: intensity,
strength and color, with the same professionalism and dedication
as the adults.
</P>
<P>
These children not only dance, but also play instruments such
as the sweet flute, the drum called dole, and the accordion.
</P>
<P>
International Folklore Festival in Brazil
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Fifth International Folklore Festival is being
held August 20-29 in Porto Alegre, the capital of the Brazilian
state of Rio Grande Do Sul, with the presence of ensembles from 16
countries.
</P>
<P>
Dancers, singers and artists of other genres from Algeria,
Argentina, Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Bulgaria, Hungary,
Israel, Italy, Mexico, Panama, Portugal, Uganda, Thailand, Ukraine
and Brazil are attending the festival.
</P>
<P>
Festival coordinator Paulo Dutra announced that simultaneously
with the festival, promoted by the United Nations Education,
Science and Culture Organization, an International Handicrafts
Fair is being held.
</P>
<P>
"Perforaciones" Wins Joaquin Mortiz Prize For a First Novel
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexican Jose Maria Velez was awarded the 1998
Joaquin Mortiz Prize For a First Novel of this country, worth
40,000 pesos (about 4,000 U.S. dollars) for his work
"Perforaciones," which will be published in October.
</P>
<P>
According to the jury of the contest, the awarded work recounts
in a monologue style the life of a painter who proposes to rescue
Emperor Moctezuma's (1446-1520) feather headdress.
</P>
<P>
Gonzalo Maria Velez is the third winner of the Joaquin Mortiz
Prize For a First Novel. The first was Alvaro Enrique with "La
Muerte de Un Instalador," and then Andres Jorge with "Pan de Mi
Cuerpo." 
</P>
</TEXT>
