<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippines and the United States have reached an
agreement to settle their months-long dispute on garments exports,
Philippine Daily Inquirer reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The United States has agreed to extend for one year a
50-million-U.S.-dollar package to compensate the Philippines for
the impact on garments exports of changes in the American rules of
origin implemented in 1996, the report said.
(Philippines-U.S.-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- European stock markets closed the week sharply down
on fears of Russian financial meltdown fueled by a big slide on
Wall Stree and with concerns over consequences of U.S. air strikes
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The London stock market went into freefall Friday wiping more
than 33 billion pounds, or some 53 billion U.S. dollars, off the
price of leading shares. (European Stocks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- New York stocks tumbled again Friday, with the Dow
Jones industrial average falling as much as 283 points as
investors reacted to turmoil in financial markets and new
political tensions around the world.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average finished the day down 77.67
points to 8,533.65, recovering from its earlier lows but still
extending the 103 point loss from the previous two days. (New
York-Stocks Down)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. government Friday reported a 24.1
billion U.S. dollars deficit for July, 6 percent less than a year
ago, but still keeping on track for the first annual budget
surplus in 29 years.
</P>
<P>
The July deficit, the gap between 143.8 billion dollars in
spending and 119.7 billion dollars in receipts, put the surplus
for the first 10 months of fiscal 1998 at 43 billion dollars,
compared with a deficit of 36.7 billion dollars for the
corresponding period of fiscal 1997. (US-Government-Surplus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda has
approved the 15 sectors in which Thailand will liberalize trade
ahead of the schedule agreed by the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC), according to a source at the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The early voluntary sectoral liberalization program involves
the removal of tariffs in nine priority sectors followed by six
other areas. It is part of a broader plan for fully free trade by
2020 in the APEC group. (Thailand-Tariff Cut)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian Government has launched major banking
restructuring moves by merging four state banks, freezing the
operations of three ailing private banks and nationalizing another
four private banks, press reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Four state banks, Bank Exim, Bapindo, Bank Bumi Daya and Bank
Dagang Negara are to merge into a new bank Bank Mandiri, Finance
Minister Bambang Subianto said here Friday. (Indonesia-Banking
Reform) 
</P>
