<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export From Bangladeshi EPZs Increases Significantly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's export earnings from
its two Export Processing Zones (EPZs) rose by 37 percent to 636
million U.S. dollars during the 1997-1998 fiscal year from 463
million dollars of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The export earnings of the Chittagong EPZ, southeastern
Bangladesh, increased by 31 percent to 450 million dollars and
that of the Dhaka EPZ by 56 percent to 186 million dollars during
the past fiscal year ending on June 30, 1998, the English-language
newspaper The Daily Star reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the total export of the EPZs cam from
ready-made garments.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong EPZ and the Dhaka EPZ exported 344 million
dollars and 119 million dollars of goods respectively in the
1996-97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The total investment in the EPZs, nevertheless, registered a
decrease to 48 million dollars during the past fiscal year from 54
million dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
As of June 1998, the cumulative amount of investment in both
EPZs stood at about 299 million dollars, with 221 million dollars
in the Chittagong EPZ and 78 million dollars in the Dhaka EPZ.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment totaling 251 million dollars accounted for
84 percent of the total investment, 26 percent of which went to
the ready-made garments industry.
</P>
<P>
South Korea invested the highest amount of some 115 million
dollars, followed by Japan with 56 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
