<HEADLINE> Myanmar Fights Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government has been
making efforts to fight against HIV/AIDS, seeking for more
cooperation from Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs) inside and
outside the country, the official paper the New Light of Myanmar
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the National AIDS Committee here Friday,
Minister for Health Major-General Ket Sein admitted that up to
now, the government has already obtained assistances and
cooperations from WHO, UNDP, UNICEF and UNAIDS and 13 NGOs inside
and outside the country.
</P>
<P>
Ket Sein, who is also chairman of the National AIDS Committee,
also urged international organizations, NGOs of neighboring
countries and domestic private organizations to provide more help.
</P>
<P>
Public education was also carried out at grass-root level and
community-based healthcare services were provided in cooperation
with NGOs in the country.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar formed the National AIDS Committee in 1989.
</P>
<P>
According to official data, there were 17,846 HIV positives and
2,337 AIDS cases in Myanmar as of the end of 1997. 
</P>
