<HEADLINE> East European Countries Understand U.S. Strike at Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria, Poland and the Czech
Republic Friday expressed their understanding of the U.S. missile
strikes at sites in Sudan and Afghanistan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Foreign Ministry spokesman Radko Vlaikov said in a
statement in Sofia that his country "understood" the U.S. strikes
at the two targets as a reaction to terrorism, the Bulgarian
Telegraph Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It is beyond doubt that international terrorism deserves
opposition and condemnation, as terrorist acts continue to threat
the lives and safety of the people in many countries, the
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The United States Thursday fired missiles to the sites in Sudan
and Afghanistan which it thought to be connected with the
terrorist acts in early August outside the U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania, killing hundreds of people and injuring thousands.
</P>
<P>
Vlaikov said Bulgaria is convinced that only with joint and
concerted efforts of the international community, can efficient
counteractions and eradication of terrorism be possible.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, the Polish Press Agency (PPA) reported in
Warsaw that "Poland and the Czech Republic understood the
U.S. strikes at the terrorist centers in Sudan and Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek told reporters,
"There has never been good response to terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Czech Foreign Minister Jan Kavan, who is on a working visit to
Poland on Friday, said the U.S. reaction against the terrorist
acts was "understandable," according to the PPA. 
</P>
