<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Asks Reversing Ruling Requiring Lawyers' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The White House Friday asked
the Supreme Court to reverse a lower court ruling that requires
government lawyers to testify in the investigation of President
Bill Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
"We stand now upon the brink of the most serious confrontation
between branches of government contemplated in our constitutional
order," the White House appeal said.
</P>
<P>
"The president's need for confidential consultations with White
House counsel in preparation for proceedings designed to remove
him from office can scarcely be questioned," it said.
</P>
<P>
A federal appeals court ruled on July 27 that Clinton's private
conversations with administration lawyers are not protected by
attorney-client privilege from grand jury questioning. The lawyers
are working for the taxpayers, not just the president, the court
said.
</P>
<P>
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist refused on August 4 to block
that ruling from taking effect, thereby clearing the way for
government lawyers' testimony while the White House pursues its
appeal.
</P>
<P>
Presidential confidant Bruce Lindsey has not yet testified
because he has been recovering from back surgery. But White House
lawyers Cheryl Mills and Lanny Breuer have gone before the grand
jury in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Independent counsel Kenneth Starr's decision to seek government
lawyers' testimony about their advice to the president "has had
for this president, and will have for future presidents, a
dramatic effect on his ability to seek the candid and forthright
advice he needs," the White House appeal to the Supreme Court said.
</P>
<P>
The lower court's ruling came on a matter "in which the
president's need for, and entitlement to, confidential legal
advice is at its zenith: in preparation for potential impeachment
proceedings, the ultimate confrontation between branches of
government," wrote lawyer Neil Eggleston, representing the White
House.
</P>
<P>
"The independent counsel is seeking to question the very
attorneys who would represent the president in the congressional
process," Eggleston wrote, adding that the ruling "grossly
inflates" Starr's authority.
</P>
<P>
Attorney-client privilege should apply for government lawyers
in criminal cases just as it does in civil cases, the appeal added.
</P>
<P>
The lower court ruling "ensures that presidents will simply
make fewer disclosures to their official counsel," Eggleston
said. "It will cause presidents to take ill-informed actions and,
through inadvertence or otherwise, perhaps run afoul of the law
more frequently."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
