<HEADLINE> US, DPRK Hold Talks in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) met in New York on
Friday with both delegations tightlipped on the topics and outcome
of the talks while promising to continue meeting on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation was led by Deputy Assistant Secretary of
State Charles Kartman and the DPRK was represented by Vice Foreign
Minister Kim Gye-kwan. The meeting at the U.S. Mission to the
United Nations started at 10:00 a.m. and ended at about 6:00
p.m. with a noon break.
</P>
<P>
Security was tightened around the Mission one day after the
U.S. launched missile attacks on Afghanistan and Sudan in response
to the August 7 twin bombings in Kenya and Tanzania. All reporters
were barred from entering the mission compound for news coverage.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said the talks may focus on the 1994 Agreed
Framework in which DPRK agreed to abandon a "nuclear weapons
program" in exchange for Western-built civilian nuclear reactors
and fuel-oil shipments.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang has complained about Washington's reluctance to
annually deliver 500,000 tons of heavy fuel oil amid Congress
blocking funds for the oil supply.
</P>
<P>
The talks were overshadowed by U.S. media reports about a spy
satellite "discovery" of a so-called nuclear complex in the DPRK.
However, the U.S. Administration has downplayed the reports.
</P>
<P>
There is a lack of evidence that the DPRK is violating the 1994
accord, the Pentagon spokesman was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
