<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Decorating Industry Thriving in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- China's interior decorating
industry is entering a robust period as the country's consumption
level has risen rapidly in the past two decades, today's China
Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
"The use of interior decorating has been extended from public
facilities into individual households, thereby embracing a large
market potential," Cao Fengquan, vice-president of the China
National Interior Decorating Association, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Decorating projects across the country earn an average total of
100 billion yuan (12.05 billion US dollars) a year, half of which
is spent by individual households, the Association told the
English newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Cao noted that as one of the country's emerging industries,
interior decorating is poised to become even more profitable.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the industry will double its current project
volume to reach a value of 200 billion yuan (24.1 billion US
dollars) by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Interior decorating was mainly applied in public facilities in
China before the 1970s when resident housing served mainly as
merely a basic form of shelter for people due to their limited
financial reserves.
</P>
<P>
China's economic reforms stirred up the interior decorating
industry, which initially focused on hotels, restaurants, shopping
malls and office buildings.
</P>
<P>
"The high-end property market maintains its status as the
biggest customer of interior decorating," Cao told the China Daily.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there are estimatedly more than 40,000 interior
decorating companies in China, which employ a total of about 2.6
million people.
</P>
<P>
"The interior decoration industry can provide a large number of
job opportunities, helping to absorb a number of laid-off
workers," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, there still exists the potential for an
outbreak of chaos to challenge this emerging industry, as shown by
the increasing numbers of customer complaints and decorators
operating illegally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
