<HEADLINE> Italy Urges Political Initiatives After U.S. Missile Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Italy Friday voiced its "clear and
unequivocal" condemnation of terrorism and called for "adequate"
political initiatives to step up international cooperation against
it.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said in a statement released Friday that
it denounces terrorism of any form and expressed understanding of
the U.S. reactions by striking the presumed terrorist bases in
Afghanistan and Sudan following the bomb attacks on the U.S.
embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement warned that attacks and counter-attacks
might trigger chain reactions and therefore called on the
international community to make concerted efforts to combat
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Terrorism is the "real danger of the future," Italian Prime
Minister Romano Prodi said, adding that Italy fully supports
battles against it.
</P>
<P>
"But, we have always said and hoped that the battle against
terrorism should be accompanied by political solutions and an
analysis that is not solely military," he told reporters from his
vacation spot in Puglia.
</P>
<P>
Prodi noted that there could be no "international coexistence
with terrorism."
</P>
<P>
One side of the question is the absolute necessity of a joint
front against terrorism; and the other is the necessity "to
continue political dialogue, without which one can go nowhere,"
the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi downplayed theories that President Bill Clinton's Sexgate
affair may have been instrumental in deciding the timing of the
missile attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
