<HEADLINE> Pippen Says He and Jordan Unlikely to Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Scottie Pippen told a radio
in Chicago during his recovering from back surgery that he does
not think either he or his friend Michael Jordan will return to
the Bulls for the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
"I do not forsee a return to the Chicago Bulls because with
each passing day it becomes more evident that I will be going
somewhere else," Pippen told WGN Radio. "The fans are great and I
know they want everyone back. But as players, we believe it's
over."
</P>
<P>
Pippen is a seven-time All-Star who has teamed with Jordan to
lead Chicago to three consecutive NBA championships and six in
eight years, making the Bull's the most powerful dynasty in
sports.
</P>
<P>
But Phil Jackson resigned as coach in June and was replaced on
July 23 by former Iowa State coach Tim Floyd. Jordn often has
said he would not play for any coach other than Jackson and
apparently repeated that in a recent conversation with Pippen.
</P>
<P>
"I believe Michael will not play again. I think he's done,"
said Pippen, who said he had spoken to Jordan within the last
week. "He will not play for anyone other than Phil Jackson."
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old Pippen will become a free agent as soon as the
NBA lockout is resolved. He had a relatively low salary last
season about 2.77 million U.S. dollars. He is believed to be
seeking a multi-year deal worth 10-15 million dollars per season
and has expressed a desire to play for the Phoenix Suns, Los
Angeles Lakers or Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
Pippen was a member of the U.S. Olympic teams in 1992 and 1996
that won gold medals and in 1996 was selected as one of the NBA's
50 Greatest Players. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
