<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, U.S. End Row on Garment Export Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and the United
States have reached an agreement to settle their months-long
dispute on garments exports, Philippine Daily Inquirer reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The United States has agreed to extend for one year a
50-million-U.S.-dollar package to compensate the Philippines for
the impact on garments exports of changes in the American rules of
origin implemented in 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Garments and Textile Export Board executive director
Escolastica Segovia was quoted as saying the Philippines was "very
satisfied" with the agreement even though the 50-million-dollar
compensation was slightly lower than the 53 million dollars
extended last year.
</P>
<P>
"The terms of compensation are more flexible and we are assured
of another year to avail of compensation from the U.S.," Segovia
said.
</P>
<P>
The garments and textile agreement would allow Philippine
exporters to shift from slow-moving products to highly-in-demand
products such as T-shirts and pants.
</P>
<P>
Segovia said the Philippines would start negotiations for the
terms of next year's compensation by December this year. The
current compensation package would be retroactive to January 1
this year.
</P>
<P>
With the settlement agreement, the Philippines has decided to
drop its plan to raise the dispute to the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was forced to compensate garments-exporting countries
like the Philippine after it tightened the entry of quota imports
in the U.S. by recognizing the products' origins from the source
of the raw material. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
