<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Urge Concerted Efforts Against TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Leading U.S. scientists
called for the development of a new, more effective vaccine and
increase in research investment for the elimination of
tuberculosis (TB) from the United States and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
The scientists, in a report released by the U.S. Center for
Disease Control and Prevention (CDCP) Thursday, said public
agencies and vaccine manufacturers need to work together to make
TB vaccine development a priority, increase basic research and
develop a clear consensus on the desirable characteristics of a
new vaccine.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say there has been only one vaccine available, the
Bacille Calmette-Guerin vaccine, but it has limited effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
"Although it prevents very serious disease in children and
probably substantially reduces childhood mortality for TB, it does
not prevent infection," said Dr. Rick O'brien, chief of a group of
experts that advise the CDCP, adding that "despite its widespread
use, it's had really limited epidemiologic impact on reducing TB
worldwide."
</P>
<P>
Other scientists in the group believe that a better vaccine is
key to eradicating the disease that has been around almost as long
as mankind.
</P>
<P>
"If we could put a man on the moon within decades back in the
1960s, I think we can eliminate TB if we develop the will to do
so," said O'brien, who called for a significant investment for the
research, particularly the large field trials necessary to
demonstrate efficacy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Tourist Industry Set September as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- In a continuing effort to turn
around the declining arrivals, Indonesia's tourist industry is
offering discounted travel packages through next month to foreign
visitors, press reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The offer is part of the industry's campaign during the period
dubbed Magic Month, beginning on August 10 and lasting through
September 24, to restore the battered tourist sector.
</P>
<P>
The discounts are being offered in 10 main tourist destinations
nationwide of West Java, East Java, Central Java/Yogyakarta, Bali,
Lombok, North Sulawesi, Batam, Bintan, North Sumatra and Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
"These packages sell for at least 30 percent of their normal
prices," chairman of the Indonesian Hotels and Restaurants
Associations Pontjo Sutowo told reporters here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Offers range from a three-day shopping package tour in Jakarta
starting at 35 U.S. dollars per night, a tour package in Central
Java and Yogyakarta at 39 U.S. dollars per night, to a four-day
adventure package in Sulawesi at 364.50 U.S. dollars per person.
</P>
<P>
National flag carrier Garuda gives a 40 percent discount on the
published fares for international and domestic airfares quoted in
foreign currency. Tickets must be bought at the point of origins
of the international visitors.
</P>
<P>
The Magic Month is the second phase of the "Let's Go to
Indonesia" program, a marketing and public relations campaign
designed to repair the tainted image of the country since
widespread rioting erupted in May this year.
</P>
<P>
The program kicked off with the Happy Day when foreign tourists
arriving on July 30 were awarded with packages of free room and
board and domestic flight tickets on Garuda.
</P>
<P>
Pontjo said the Magic Month might be extended to two or three
months, depending on the future situation.
</P>
<P>
After the May riots, tourist arrivals declined sharply and
several countries issued travel warnings to their citizens. In
Jakarta alone, nearly 1,200 people died and businesses throughout
the city were gutted during three days of chaos.
</P>
<P>
Pontjo said that through improved marketing and efforts to
shift perceptions of Indonesia abroad, the "Let's Go to Indonesia"
campaign hoped to turn international focus on the nation and the
low value of its rupiah currency to an advantage. The rupiah has
sunk by 80 percent of its value from the middle of last year
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Only 1.3 million visitors traveled to Indonesia in the first
five months of 1998, bringing 1.4 billion U.S. dollars in revenue.
</P>
<P>
Some 5.2 million visitors arrived last year, bringing in 6.77
billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0217 </DOCNO>
