<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin, National People's Congress Standing
Committee Chairman Li Peng, Premier Zhu Rongji and other senior
Party and government leaders met a group of scientists and
teachers yesterday in the Great Hall of the People in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the group, Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said the
State strategy of creating an economic take-off through science
and education will put China in a better position to face the
opportunities and challenges of the new centennial
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin's scheduled visits to Japan
and Russia in early September have been postponed due to the
immensity of flood control and disaster relief efforts in China.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President and Party General Secretary Jiang Zemin
made a phone call on Thursday evening to Minister of Health Zhang
Wenkang, urging concentrated efforts to prevent epidemic outbreaks
in the flood-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, made several phone calls to leaders of
flood-ravaged Heilongjiang Province and to the minister of water
resources in recent days, inquiring about the situation of major
Chinese rivers.
</P>
<P>
-- A Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman yesterday reaffirmed
China's clear stance of condemning all terrorist activities while
responding to questions raised by reporters about U.S. missile
strikes in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao yesterday spoke highly of
Sino-Ghanaian friendly relations and voiced his appreciation of
the Ghanaian government's adherence to the "one China" policy.
</P>
<P>
Hu made the remarks during a meeting with a delegation of
Ghanaian women led by Nana Konadu Agyeman-Rawlings, the first lady
and president of the 31st of December Women's movement of Ghana.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Harbin, the capital of Northeast China's Heilongjiang
province, withstood its heaviest flood onslaught yesterday
afternoon as the third flood crest of Songhua River pounded
embankments around its riverfront.
</P>
<P>
The flood peak hit 120.82 meters and roared on with a magnitude
of 17,400 cubic meters per second as of 3 p.m. yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- The Beijing-based Association for Relations Across the
Taiwan Straits (Arats) shrugged off criticism from Taiwan over a
recent kidnapping case and sent a third letter urging further
talks with its counterpart, the Straits Exchange Foundation
(Sef).
</P>
<P>
Lin Ti-chuan and her boyfriend, both Taiwanese, were reportedly
kidnapped in the course of a business dispute with the boyfriend's
mainland partners. Lin later died in Haicheng in Liaoning
Province. 
