<HEADLINE> he082208 - Aussie Armed Forces to Introduce Part-time Soldiering: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Defense Force,
the nation's armed forces, would introduce flexible work
arrangements that would allow military personnel to work from home
or part-time, the Sydney Morning Herald reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The arrangements also would allow personnel to take breaks from
difficult periods of service and negotiate flexible hours with
their commanding officers.
</P>
<P>
The changes have been interpreted as an attempt to make the
military more attractive to people with families, and to retain
staff wanting to pursue an education or training.
</P>
<P>
The arrangements would apply to the nation's army, navy and air
force, and were expected to be in place by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The number of Australian servicemen totals 57,000.
</P>
<P>
Arch Bevis, defense spokesman for the Australian Labor Party,
said the flexibility which the Australian federal government was
introducing was good but it had been flagged in 1994 by Paul
Keating's labor government, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
