<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chretien, Bouchard Claim Victory Over Court Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien said here Friday that the Supreme Court of Canada's ruling
against Quebec's separation was a victory for all Canadians.
</P>
<P>
"The ruling yesterday by the Supreme Court of Canada is of
extraordinary importance," Chretien told a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
"It's not a victory for governments or politicians. It is a
victory for all Canadians. It protects the legal and democratic
rights of citizens of our country for the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
The top court ruled Thursday that Quebec does not have the right to
separate unilaterally either under the Canadian constitution or
international law.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the court also noted that if a "clear" majority of Quebecers
vote on a "clear" question to get out of Canada, then the federal
government and other provinces should negotiate with Quebec and let
it go.
</P>
<P>
In his first response the day after the ruling, Quebec Premier
Lucien Bouchard, like his arch-rival Chretien, also claimed victory.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is something that is comforting the sovereigntist
project and, as such, it should be helpful in the next election and
mainly in the next referendum," he said in Quebec City, capital of
the French-speaking province.
</P>
<P>
Bouchard said that the separatists lost three to four percentage
lead in the last days of the referendum campaign in fall 1995
mainly because of uncertainly about whether Ottawa would negotiate
the breakup of the country.
</P>
<P>
"These Quebeckers find themselves reassured today: their Yes vote
will force Canada to negotiate," Bouchard noted.
</P>
<P>
Bouchard has already said that Quebec would hold another
referendum on its independence if the separatist side can win.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's ruling has been a key part of Ottawa's unity strategy
since it barely won a Quebec referendum in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
Ottawa hoped that the ruling by the top court will persuade soft
nationalists in Quebec to support the unity of the country.
</P>
<P>
It also sent a strong message to hardcore separatists in Quebec
that a vote for sovereignty would mean a prolonged and painful
process of divorce.
</P>
<P>
Ottawa asked the court for its opinion on three deceptively
simple questions. Can Quebec unilaterally declare independence
under domestic law? Does international law give Quebec a right to
secede? If two laws conflict, which prevail?
</P>
<P>
The court ruled that Quebec does not have the right to go
unilaterally under either domestic or international law, and that
there is no conflict between the two. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
