<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Balance of Payment Surplus Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' balance of
payment surplus (BOP) further dropped to 1.4 billion U.S. dollars
as of end-July this year from the month-ago level of 1.6 billion
dollars, according to the central bank.
</P>
<P>
In a report published here Saturday, the central bank said the
seven-month BOP surplus also stood much lower than the two-year
high of 2.1 billion dollars as of mid-May this year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the decline, central bank officials said the latest BOP
level was still a strong turnaround from the 3.36-billion-dollar
deficit in 1997.
</P>
<P>
They said the central bank had to shell out dollars in July to
cover the usual month-end debt obligations and that there was a
slight reversal of the trade surplus sen during the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
BOP accounts the flow of resources between the local economy
and the rest of the world. It systematically records the foreign
exchange flows arising from economic transactions such as trade
and portfolio investments during a given period.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in the BOP position from the end-1997 level was
due not only to the narrowing of the trade gap but also due to the
continued inflows from investments and loan proceeds, the central
bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
