<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Company Engineers Rootworm-Resistant Corn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. biotechnology company
claimed Friday that it had genetically engineered a corn that can
resist rootworm, a pest that does major damage to corn crops in
North America.
</P>
<P>
Eric Sachs, business leader for Monsanto Co., said in a
statement that commercial introduction of rootworm-resistant corn
seeds by the biotechnology company would probably come in the year
2001 or 2002, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Corn rootworm does an estimated one billion U.S. dollar damage
annually on about 15 million acres in North America. Farmers spend
about 150 million U.S. dollars each year on a number of chemical
insecticides.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that the damage is done by the larvae of two
beetle species, the western corn rootworm (diabrotica virgifera)
and the northern corn rootworm (diabrotica barberi).
</P>
<P>
The adult female beetles prefer to lay eggs in cornfields,
where they hatch in the spring at the same time corn seedlings are
growing. The feeding on corn roots inhibits the plant's ability to
take up water and nutrients and to stand straight, they explained.
</P>
<P>
In field trials this summer, the corn demonstrated "excellent
control" of rootworm, and none of the plants in the tests fell
over," said Dr. Jay Pershing, the Mosanto entomologist leading the
research.
</P>
<P>
Monsanto Co., which has been working since 1989 to develop a
corn seed that resists rootworm, said it would be the first to
introduce rootworm-resistant corn seeds since there are currently
no such seeds available in the market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Launches Banking Restructuring Moves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Government has
launched major banking restructuring moves by merging four state
banks, freezing the operations of three ailing private banks and
nationalizing another four private banks, press reports said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Four state banks, Bank Exim, Bapindo, Bank Bumi Daya and Bank
Dagang Negara are to merge into a new bank Bank Mandiri, Finance
Minister Bambang Subianto said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government is to strengthen the capital structure of Bank
Mandiri, he said, adding that it has also appointed Deutsche Bank
an adviser and consultant to help restructure the country's
non-listed troubled banks.
</P>
<P>
The seven private banks were placed under the Indonesian
Banking Restructuring Agency (IBRA) supervision on April 4 because
they had received over 2 trillion rupiah (200 million U.S.
dollars) of Bank Indonesia, the central bank, liquidity credits,
500 percent more than their assets.
</P>
<P>
Subianto announced the nationalization of four banks under the
supervision of IBRA, Bank Central Asia (BCA), Bank Danamon, Bank
PDFCI and Bank Tiara.
</P>
<P>
BCA, which was hit by a recent massive run on deposits, is the
country's largest private bank.
</P>
<P>
"The government has received statements from owners of the four
banks about their willingness to hand over funds and assets. The
deadline for the hand-over is September 21, 1998," Subianto said.
</P>
<P>
The government also said it froze the operations of Bank
Modern, Bank Umum Nasional and Bank Dagang Nasional Indonesia,
bringing the number of banks frozen so far this year to 10.
</P>
<P>
Subianto added that the seven banks whose operations were
frozen in April would be liquidated soon. The seven banks are Bank
Surya, Bank Subentra, Bank Kredit Asia, Bank Pelita, Hokindo Bank,
Deka Bank and Centris International Bank.
</P>
<P>
Banking reform is one of the top priorities set by the
government and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) under an
IMF-led 43 billion U.S. dollars bailout agreement as the poor
banking system remains a major contributor to the country's
prolonged economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
