<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Cuts Overnight Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines has decided to cut its current overnight borrowing and
lending rates by two percentage points with the Philippine peso
stabilizing at the local foreign exchange market, a newspaper
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The overnight borrowing rate will be reduced effective Monday
from 18 percent to 16 percent, and the lending rate will be
reduced from 20 percent to 18 percent, the Philippine Star said.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson was quoted as saying the
Monetary Board, the bank's highest decision-making body, decided
to bring down overnight rates in recognition of the peso's
recovery and the easing of speculative pressures.
</P>
<P>
Singson emphasized that "the increase in our overnight rates is
only temporary."
</P>
<P>
But he added that the authority is "ready to respond quickly in
the event of renewed speculative attacks."
</P>
<P>
The central bank resorted to increasing its key overnight rates
to quell speculation against the peso more than a week ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
