<HEADLINE> Canadian Dollar Drops Below 65 U.S. Cents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian dollar dropped below
65 U.S. cents for the first time at the North American market
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar plunged about half a cent to an all-time low of
64.83 U.S. cents early in the day.
</P>
<P>
Though the Bank of Canada rushed to its rescue, the dollar
ended the day 64.86 U.S. cents, another record low.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters here, Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien said that he was "concerned" about the fall of the
country's currency.
</P>
<P>
"Like everybody, I'm surprised and concerned, and I'd ask the
financial community to look at the Canadian situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"All the fundamentals are there," he said, noting that the
Canadian economy remains strong with a shrinking deficit, low
inflation and a stable jobless rate. 
