<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Hit by Increased Stomach Bugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- An upsurge in stomach bugs
has troubled New Zealanders this year with Wellington, capital of
the country, as the worst affected area.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion, a Wellington-based newspaper, reported Saturday
that the Environmental and Scientific Research Institute of New
Zealand, which has been monitoring the high level of bacterial
outbreaks, confirmed Friday that 1998 is shaping up to be a record
year for campylobacter and salmonella.
</P>
<P>
Institute public health physician Michael Baker said that if
the rate continues there would be about 11,500 cases of
campylobacter and 2,000 cases of salmonella by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
For the first seven months this year 6,369 cases of
campylobacter and 1,329 cases of salmonella were notified, up 30
percent and 68 percent respectively from the figures in the
corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
On a measurement of cases for each 100,000 people, the
Wellington health district fared worst with 567 cases of
campylobacter, salmonella and yersinia.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Baker said that a likely theory for the big increase is the
 warm winter this year, the warmest since records were started in
1853.
</P>
<P>
The bacterial bugs are transmitted by contaminated food or
water. The illness usually lasts about a week. Symptoms are severe
stomach cramps, diarrhea, nausea and vomiting.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Baker urged people to develop good personal hygiene habits
in order to avoid illness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
