<HEADLINE> Sudan Asks Security Council to Discuss U.S. Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Sudan Friday called for
"an emergent meeting" by the U.N. Security Council to discuss
Thursday's U.S. missile strikes on the African country.
</P>
<P>
Describing the U.S. move as "the flagrant American aggression,"
Sudan also asked the Security Council to "take the necessary
measures to ensure the non-recurrence of such criminal acts of
aggression."
</P>
<P>
The appeal, first of its kind since the U.S. attacks, was
contained in a letter to President of the Security Council Danilo
Turk from Bishop Gobrial Roric, state minister of Sudan's Ministry
of External Relations.
</P>
<P>
Elfatih Erwa, Sudan's permanent representative to the United
Nations, conveyed the letter to the council president.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, Erwa voiced his intention to ask the 15-member
Security Council to send a fact-finding mission to Khatoum, the
Sudanese capital, to confirm its claim that the plant bombed by
the United States was not involved in chemical warfare activities.
</P>
<P>
The United States Thursday launched missile strikes on Sudan
and Afghanistan in what was seen as a retaliation to the August 7
twin bombings in Kenya and Tanzania, which killed 257 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
