<HEADLINE> Action Urged to Allow Return of Uprooted Kosovars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Assistant High Commissioner for Refugees has called for immediate
action to allow the return of more than 230,000 people uprooted
by the conflict in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Soren Jessen-Petersen made the call Friday as he left Kosovo
after a two-day visit to assess the situation of displacement and
the level of destruction in the Serb province and to urge the
authorities to restore stability, a U.N. spokesman said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR official underlined the urgent need for adequate
arrangements to reassure these people's safe return.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, with an area of some 10,000 square km, has a population
of over 2 million, 90 percent of whom are ethnic Albanians. The
conflict between Albanian separatists and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia has been escalating since February.
</P>
<P>
In addition to a large number of people displaced internally,
there are about 30,000 Kosovar refugees registered in Montenegro
and 14,000 in neighboring Albania as a result of the conflict.
</P>
