<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss National Bank Refuses to Contribute to New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss National Bank (SNB) has
decided not to contribute to the 1.25-billion-dollar Holocaust
settlement between two major banks and Jewish claimants.
</P>
<P>
"The Swiss National Bank will not make a financial contribution
to the costs of the settlement between Swiss banks and
representatives of class-action suits in the United States," the
Swiss central bank said in a statement issued Friday in the Swiss
capital of Berne at the end of its supervisory board meeting.
</P>
<P>
SNB Chairman Hans Meyer said that the central bank as a public
institution could not and did not want to take part in a
settlement between private parties. The SNB's helping to finance
the accord would have lent an official character to the settlement
that was not in the overall interest of the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss government has also refused to help finance the deal,
which protects the Swiss government and industry, the SNB, and
other Swiss banks from possible boycotts by U.S. cities and
states.
</P>
<P>
UBS and Credit Suisse, Switzerland's two biggest banks which
made the deal with the claimants on August 12 in New York, have
said they would like other firms and the central bank who benefit
from the deal to contribute to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
The government issued a statement Friday welcoming the SNB's
decision not to make a contribution.
</P>
<P>
"This decision flows seamlessly from the position taken thus
far by the government and National Bank that the state and its
institutions will not take part in an out-of-court settlement,"
the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980822.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
