<HEADLINE> Talbott to Hold "Critical Meetings" with India, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott will hold "critical meetings" with Indian and
Pakistani envoys next week to discuss their nuclear tests, the
State Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting with Indian special envoy Jaswant Singh will be
held in Washington Monday while the meeting with Pakistani Foreign
Secretary Shamshad Ahmad will take place in London Tuesday, State
Department spokesman James Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"These are critical meetings," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
Talbott has held several rounds of separate meetings with Singh
and Ahmad, most recently in the region last month.
</P>
<P>
A senior U.S. official said that Washington hoped for something
productive from next week's meetings. These meetings "are probably
the last before we have to take a decision on the President's
visit in November," he said.
</P>
<P>
Plans for President Bill Clinton to visit India and Pakistan
were put on hold after first India and then Pakistan conducted
nuclear tests in May. 
