<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Keeps First Surplus in 29 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government Friday
reported a 24.1 billion U.S. dollars deficit for July, 6 percent
less than a year ago, but still keeping on track for the first
annual budget surplus in 29 years.
</P>
<P>
The July deficit, the gap between 143.8 billion dollars in
spending and 119.7 billion dollars in receipts, put the surplus
for the first 10 months of fiscal 1998 at 43 billion dollars,
compared with a deficit of 36.7 billion dollars for the
corresponding period of fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal year ends on September 30. Analysts believed that
August will produce another deficit but September, when quarterly
income tax payments are due from businesses and some individuals,
will bring a substantial surplus.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration forecast in May a 39.1 billion
dollars surplus for the whole fiscal 1998, the first surplus since
1969. Two months later, the Congressional Budget Office said the
surplus should amount to as high as 63 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. federal deficit hit a record 290 billion dollars in
1992.
</P>
<P>
According to the report Friday, the largest spending categories
for July were: Social Security, 36.4 billion dollars; Department
of Health and Human Services programs such as Medicare and
Medicaid, 32.5 billion dollars; the military, 24.6 billion
dollars, and interest on the public debt, 20.8 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
