<HEADLINE> IFC Launches Greek Drachma Global Notes Offering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) Friday launched a 15 billion Greek drachma (some
49.5 million U.S. dollar) Global Medium Term Notes offering.
</P>
<P>
The three-year notes carry an annual coupon of 8.625 percent
per annum and an issue price of 101.22 percent. The proceeds of
the issue will be swapped into U.S. dollar floating rate funds.
</P>
<P>
The lead manager is Morgan Stanley and the syndicate group of
some European and Northern American banks.
</P>
<P>
This transaction is the seventh borrowing for the new fiscal
year, which began on July 1 this year, and brings the IFC's market
borrowings for 1999 fiscal year to about 637.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is a member of the World Bank Group, financing private
sector projects in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
