<HEADLINE> Eoropean Stock Markets Nosedive with Fears of Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets closed the
week sharply down on fears of Russian financial meltdown fuelled
by a big slide on Wall Stree and with concerns over consequences
of U.S. air strikes on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The London stock market went into freefall Friday wiping more
than 33 billion pounds, or some 53 billion U.S. dollars, off the
price of leading shares.
</P>
<P>
Traders were gripped by fears the U.S. attacks on Afghanistan
and Sudan could escalate and rumors of a fresh round of currency
crises swept around the world, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street opened with dramatic falls on the Dow Jones index
and the London market was driven further into the red during the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
At one point the FTSE 100 fell to 5455.1, down 212.3. By the
close, however, the FTSE had rallied slightly to close at 5477
down 190.4.
</P>
<P>
The Dow continued its nosedive after London's close boding
badly for Monday's market opening in London, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Peter Oppenheimer, chief investment strategist at HSBC
Securities, was quoted as saying: "All the markets in Europe are
falling. The Asian contagion has spread to Latin America and other
commodity producing countries. We're all wondering where it will
end. The U.S. air strikes just add to these concerns."
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, leading German shares dropped sharply after a
slump at opening on Wall Street, too, with the Russian financial
crisis continuing to weigh heavily on international markets.
</P>
<P>
The leading Dax index closed 324 points lower at 5163.51, a
drop of 6.2 percent. However, the Xetra Dax, reflecting electronic
trading which continued after floor trading finished, recovered in
late trade to close down 209.4 points at 5190.6.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French stocks also showed severe losses in late trade
as U.S. and Latin American markets joined the global slide. The
leading Cac-40 index fell 143.61 points, or 3.6 percent, to close
at 3943.68.
</P>
<P>
Dealers were said to be braced for a devaluation Venezuela's
bolivar, which has again rattled markets right across the region.
The shares had been hit hard earlier amid continuing worries about
the economic instability in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Today's pull back was heightened by the upcoming monthly
liquidation. With only one more day of trading before the
beginning of the new trading month, investors are selling off
their equity, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
"Monday will be the last day for liquidating investment
positions, which means many people will sell their shares before
then, so as to buy on credit when the new month begins on
Tuesday," Jean Faivre, a trader at CLC bourse, was quoted by local
media as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
