<HEADLINE> S. Africa's ANC to Lose Ground in Election: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) will lose ground in the 1999
general election, according to a survey released Friday.
</P>
<P>
Markdata said in a statement t(at the poll indicated that 57
percent of voters would favor the ANC-led alliance with South
African Communist Party and the Congress of South African Trade
Unions, a 5.5 percentage points drop from the 62.5 percent in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The National Party (NP), expected to win only 10.7 percent in
next year's election, will be seriously challenged by the
Democratic Party (DP), which is expected to win 10 percent, said
the survey conducted in July.
</P>
<P>
The NP won more than 20 percent of the votes in the 1994
election.
</P>
<P>
The racial breakdown indicates that the ANC is by far the most
popular party among blacks with 72.9 percent, followed by Inkatha
Freedom Party (IFP) with 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The NP enjoys the most support among the colored with 42.4
percent, followed by the ANC (29.6 percent) and the DP (17.7
percent).
</P>
<P>
Among Indians, support for the DP and NP is at 32.4 percent
and 31.4 percent res0eatively. Both are clearly ahead of the ANC
(19.4 percent) and the United Democratic Movement (UDM) with 10.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
Among whites, the DP has established a dominant position at 46
percent, eclipsing the formerly dominant NP (24.6 percent) by a
substantial margin. The ANC has the support of only 2.6 percent
of the white population.
</P>
<P>
A study examining trends in party support from 1994 to 1998
suggests that the ANC has since 1997 lost a great deal of the
nominal or uncommitted support which it used to attract, Markdata
said.
</P>
<P>
The NP has lost support quite dramatically since its departure
from the government of national unity and the resignation of F. W.
de Klet+ as its leader.
</P>
<P>
The IFP appears to be at roughly the same level of support as
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the success stories are the DP, the
Pan Africanist Congress and the newly established UDM. 
</P>
</TEXT>
